{"title_page": "Bella Vista de Bah\u00eda Blanca", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Bella Vistas\n| image = Bella Vista de Bah\u00eda Blanca logo.svg\n| image_size = 130px\n| fullname = Club Bella Vista\n| nickname = ''Los Gallegos, la loma, albiverdes'' \n| founded = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1921|4|18}}\n| ground = Estadio Ignacio Nicol\u00e1s, <br> [[Bah\u00eda Blanca]], [[Buenos Aires Province]]\n| capacity = 4,000\n| chairman = Gustavo Lari\n| manager = Carlos Maria Mungo\n| league =  [[Torneo Federal B]]\n| season = [[2016 in Argentine football|2016]]\n| position = 3 of Zona 2\n|pattern_la1=|pattern_b1=_rightsashonwhite|pattern_ra1=|leftarm1=ffffff|body1=009933|rightarm1=ffffff|shorts1=ffffff|socks1=ffffff\n|pattern_la2=|pattern_b2=_whiterightsash|pattern_ra2=|leftarm2=009933|body2=009933|rightarm2=009933|shorts2=009933|socks2=009933\n|\n}}\n\n'''Club Bella Vista''' is an [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[association football|football]] club located in the city of [[Bah\u00eda Blanca]], in [[Buenos Aires Province]]. The team currently plays in [[Torneo Federal B]], the regionalised 4th level of the [[Argentine football league system]].\n\nThe most notable player in the club history is [[Alfio Basile]], who went on to become manager of the [[Argentina national football team]], leading them to two [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] titles.\nRodrigo Palacio es otro jugador surgido en club y en el cual form\u00f3 parte del plantel del torneo argentino B.\nFue compa\u00f1ero en ese mismo equipo de Mart\u00edn \"gula\" Aguirre (ex River y Godoy Cruz) surgido de la cantera del club bahiense.\nTambi\u00e9n es destacado mencionar al ex futbolista Jorge \"laucha\" Recio con pasado \"albiverde\" y con futuro en River y la selecci\u00f3n Argentina de f\u00fatbol.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://clubbellavista.blogspot.com/ Bella Vista blog]\n\n{{Torneo Argentino B}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bella Vista de Bahia Blanca}}\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1921]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Buenos Aires Province]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in Argentina]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-footyclub-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Bella Vistas\n| image = Bella Vista de Bah\u00eda Blanca logo.svg\n| image_size = 130px\n| fullname = Club Bella Vista\n| nickname = ''Los Gallegos, Albiverdes''\n| founded = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1921|4|18}}\n| ground = Estadio Ignacio Nicol\u00e1s, <br> [[Bah\u00eda Blanca]], [[Buenos Aires Province]]\n| capacity = 4,000\n| chairman = Gustavo Lari\n| manager = Carlos Maria Mungo\n| league =  [[Torneo Federal B]]\n| season = [[2016 in Argentine football|2016]]\n| position = 3 of Zona 2\n|pattern_la1=|pattern_b1=_rightsashonwhite|pattern_ra1=|leftarm1=ffffff|body1=009933|rightarm1=ffffff|shorts1=ffffff|socks1=ffffff\n|pattern_la2=|pattern_b2=_whiterightsash|pattern_ra2=|leftarm2=009933|body2=009933|rightarm2=009933|shorts2=009933|socks2=009933\n|\n}}\n\n'''Club Bella Vista''' is an [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[association football|football]] club located in the city of [[Bah\u00eda Blanca]], in [[Buenos Aires Province]]. The team currently plays in [[Torneo Federal B]], the regionalised 4th level of the [[Argentine football league system]].\n\nThe most notable player in the club history is [[Alfio Basile]], who went on to become manager of the [[Argentina national football team]], leading them to two [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] titles.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://clubbellavista.blogspot.com/ Bella Vista blog]\n\n{{Torneo Argentino B}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bella Vista de Bahia Blanca}}\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1921]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Buenos Aires Province]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in Argentina]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-footyclub-stub}}\n", "name_user": "200.81.175.160", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bella_Vista_de_Bah%C3%ADa_Blanca"}
{"title_page": "Ford F-Series (eighth generation)", "text_new": "{{main|Ford F-Series}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Eighth generation\n| image = Ford F-150 -- 09-07-2009.jpg\n| manufacturer = [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]]\n| production = (1986\u20131991) USA, Mexico, Canada and Venezuela<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=0OMDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA97&lpg=PA97&dq=ford+f-series+\"august+1986\"+1987#v=onepage&q=ford%20f-series%20%22august%201986%22%201987&f=false |title = Popular Mechanics|publisher = Hearst Magazines|date = August 1986}}</ref> <br>(1987-1992) Australia<ref name=\"au used car advice\">https://www.motoring.com.au/used-car-advice-ford-f-series-1985-92-1945/</ref> <br>(1988-1992) Argentina<br>(1993-1996) Brazil<br> (1993-1996) Argentina (Brazilian trim model)\n| assembly = [[Cuautitlan]], Mexico<br />[[Kansas City, Missouri]], USA<br />[[Norfolk Assembly|Norfolk, Virginia]], USA<br />[[Twin Cities Assembly Plant|St. Paul, Minnesota]], USA<br/> [[General Pacheco]], [[Argentina]]<br />[[S\u00e3o Bernardo do Campo]], [[Brazil]]<br />[[Louisville, Kentucky]], USA<br />[[Wayne, Michigan]], USA<br />[[Oakville, Ontario]], Canada<br />[[Melbourne]], [[Australia]] ([[Broadmeadows Assembly]], [[Ford Australia]]) <ref name=\"au used car advice\" />\n| body_style = 2-door [[pickup truck|pickup]]<br>2-door [[pickup truck#Extended cab|extended cab]] chassis<br />4-door [[chassis cab]]<br>2-door [[pickup truck#No bed (cab and chassis or chassis-cab)|chassis cab]]\n| engine = '''[[Petrol engine|Petrol]]'''<br>{{convert|232|cuin|L|1|disp=flip|abbr=on}} ''[[Ford Essex V6 engine (Canadian)#3.8|Essex]]'' V6 (Ford F-150, Mexico)<br/>{{convert|300|cuin|L|1|disp=flip|abbr=on}} ''[[Ford Straight-6 engine#300|300]]'' I6<br /> {{convert|302|cuin|L|1|disp=flip|abbr=on}}'' [[Ford Windsor engine#302|5.0 Windsor]]'' V8<br />{{convert|351|cuin|L|1|disp=flip|abbr=on}} ''[[Ford Windsor engine#351W|Windsor]]'' V8<br />{{convert|460|cuin|L|1|disp=flip|abbr=on}} ''[[Ford 385 engine|385]]'' V8<br />4.1 MWM \"X10\" Diesel I6 ([[Brazil]] and [[Argentina]])<br />4.1 MWM \"X10\" Turbo Diesel I6 ([[Brazil]] and [[Argentina]])<br />{{convert|420|cuin|L|1|disp=flip|abbr=on}} ''[[International Harvester IDI#6.9L|International IDI]]'' Diesel V8 <br />{{convert|444|cuin|L|1|disp=flip|abbr=on}} ''[[International Harvester IDI#7.3L|International IDI]]'' Diesel V8\n| transmission = {{ubl\n                 | '''[[Automatic transmission|Automatic]]'''\n                 | 3-Speed Ford [[Ford C6 transmission|C6]]\n                 | 4-Speed Ford AOD\n                 | 4-Speed Ford [[Ford C6 transmission#E4OD|E4OD]] (1989-91)\n                 | '''[[Manual transmission|Manual]]'''\n                 | 4-Speed [[Borg-Warner]] ''T18''\n                 | 4-Speed [[Borg-Warner]] ''T19'' (1987)\n                 | 5-Speed [[Mazda]] [[Mazda M5OD transmission|M5OD]] (1988-91)\n                 | 5-Speed [[List of ZF transmissions|ZF]] S5-42 (1988-91)\n                 }}\n| predecessor = [[Ford F-Series seventh generation]] (1979\u20131986)\n| successor = [[Ford F-Series ninth generation]] (1992\u20131996)\n}}\n\nThe '''eighth generation of the [[Ford F-Series]]''' is a line of pickup trucks and light- to medium-duty commercial trucks produced by [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] from 1986 to 1991. While the 1980 cab and chassis was carried over to the new model, the 1987 model was more streamlined, and maintenance items were made simpler. The exterior was facelifted with new composite headlamps, a more aerodynamic front end, and circular fenders. Inside, the interior was given a complete redesign.  Rear [[antilock brakes]] were now standard, the first pickup truck to boast this.  For the first time, all models were produced with straight-sided Styleside beds; the Flareside bed was discontinued except for a small number of early 1987 models using leftover 1986 beds with new circular fenders. In 1991 Ford premiered the 9th gen tail lights (the white reverse light was decreased in size) on the last year of the 8th generation.\n\n==Trims==\n[[File:F250 utility service truck.jpeg|thumb|Ford F-250 Utility service truck]]\n*Custom - Included: Vinyl upholstery, black steering wheel, chrome front bumper, black grille, hubcaps, foldaway mirrors, and an electronic AM radio with digital clock and two speakers.\n*XL - Added: Cloth and vinyl upholstery, swingaway mirrors, front bumper rub strip, color-keyed floor mat, a door trim panel with map pocket, and a color-keyed headliner.\n*XLT Lariat - Added: Cloth upholstery, chrome grille, sport wheel covers, tinted glass, carpeting, and leather wrapped steering wheel.\n*Nite (1992)\n\nFor 1992, a \"Nite\" trim package was introduced. It included all blacked-out exterior trim, either a pink or blue/purple stripe, and a \"Nite\" decal on the sides of the cargo box.\n\n== Models ==\n[[File:UHI DC5692.JPG|thumb|Ford F-350 [[U-Haul]] truck in [[Hampton, VA]].]]\n\nEighth-generation Ford F-Series models are:\n* '''F-150''': 1/2 ton (6,250&nbsp;lb [[GVWR]] max)\n* '''F-250''': light-duty 3/4 ton (7,700&nbsp;lb GVWR max)\n* '''F-250HD''': 3/4 ton (8,800&nbsp;lb GVWR max)\n* '''F-350''': 1 ton (10,000&nbsp;lb GVWR max)\n* '''F-Super Duty''': Class 4 truck (14,500&nbsp;lb GVWR max)\n\nThe new-for-1987 F-Super Duty was essentially a [[Truck classification#Class 4|Class 4 truck]] built as a chassis cab, with an aftermarket bed (specific to its future use) added after the truck was built. The F-Super Duty came with dual fuel tanks with a dash-mounted toggle switch to switch between each tank, while using only a single fuel gauge. It came with a [[Power take-off|PTO]] used to power attachments, such as winches or a dump bed, directly from the transmission. F-Super Duty models were rated at about {{convert|15000|lb|abbr=on}} [[GVWR]] and came with either the standard 7.5&nbsp;L (460&nbsp;CID) gas V8 or the optional 7.3&nbsp;L (444&nbsp;CID) diesel V8. All wheels were 10-lug with dual wheels in the rear. This model should not be confused with the later [[Ford Super Duty|Super Duty]] commercial line of trucks starting with the 1999 model year.\n\n==Powertrain and chassis==\nIn a move to further update the F-Series engine lineup, the 4.9&nbsp;L inline-6 was converted to fuel injection for 1987. A year later, Ford became the first pickup truck manufacturer to sell a fully non-carbureted engine lineup as the 5.8&nbsp;L V8 and 7.5&nbsp;L V8 also gained [[fuel injection]](the 5.0&nbsp;L V8 had gained fuel injection as an option for 1985 and was made standard in 1986). For 1988, the diesel V8 from International (Navistar) was enlarged to from 420 to 444 cubic inches (6.9 to 7.3 L); this allowed for an increase to {{convert|180|hp|abbr=on}} and {{convert|365|ft.lbf|N.m|abbr=on}} of torque.\n\nWhile the dated 3-speed column-mounted manual transmission was discontinued, much of the rest of the transmission lineup carried over from the 1980-1986 trucks. In 1988, the five-speed ZF S5-42 replaced the Borg-Warner T19 in F-250 and F-350 models. For the F-150 and light-duty F-250, the heavier-duty Borg-Warner T18 4-speed manual remained available, while the Mazda-built [[Mazda M5OD transmission|M5OD]] 5-speed manual was added to the model lineup for 4.9&nbsp;L inline-6 and 5.0&nbsp;L V8-equipped models.\n\nFour-wheel-drive improvements included the addition of automatic locking hubs for the F-150 in 1989. Models with the 5.0L V8 also had an option of a \"Touch Drive\" electronic transfer case.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\nFrom 1980 through 1996, Ford offered a four-wheel-drive swing arm independent front suspension called [[Twin Traction Beam]] (TTB). Based on its two-wheel-drive twin I-beam suspension from 1965, Ford mounted a [[Dana 44]] differential in the driver-side (front) axle beam and transmitted torque to the passenger-side wheel with a double U-jointed axleshaft. Radius arms and coil springs were still used on the F-150, while the four-wheel-drive F-250 and F-350 got leaf springs. The F-250 received TTB [[Dana 50]] axles, and the F-350 a solid [[Dana 60]] axle.\n\n'''Engines:'''\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 88%;\"\n|-\n! Name !! Production !! Engine type/Displacement !! Power !! Torque !! Fuel Delivery\n|-\n|'''[[Ford Straight-6 engine#300|300 Six]]'''||1987-1991 ||{{convert|300|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} I6 || {{convert|145|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} ||{{convert|265|lbft|Nm||abbr=on}} || EFI\n|-\n|'''[[Ford Windsor engine#302|5.0 Windsor]]'''|| 1987-1991 ||{{convert|302|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} V8 ||  {{convert|185|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} || {{convert|270|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}}|| EFI\n|-\n|'''[[Ford Windsor engine#351W|5.8 Windsor]]'''|| 1987 ||  {{convert|351|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} V8  || {{convert|210|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} ||  {{convert|305|lbft|Nm||abbr=on}} ||4-bbl carburetor\n|-\n|'''[[Ford Windsor engine#351W|5.8 Windsor]]'''|| 1988-1991 || {{convert|351|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} V8  || {{convert|210|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} ||  {{convert|315|lbft|Nm||abbr=on}} ||EFI\n\n|-\n|''' [[Ford 385 engine|460 V8]] '''|| 1987 ||{{convert|460|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} V8 || {{convert|225|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} || {{convert|362|lbft|Nm||abbr=on}} ||4-bbl carburetor\n\n|-\n|''' [[Ford 385 engine|460 V8]] '''|| 1988-1991 ||{{convert|460|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} V8 || {{convert|225|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} || {{convert|390|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}}||EFI\n\n|-\n|'''  [[International Harvester IDI#6.9L|International 6.9L IDI V8]]'''|| 1987 ||{{convert|420|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} Diesel V8 || {{convert|170|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} || {{convert|315|lbft|Nm||abbr=on}} ||Indirect fuel injection\n\n|-\n|'''  [[International Harvester IDI#7.3L|International 7.3L IDI V8]] '''|| 1988-1991 ||{{convert|444|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} Diesel V8 || {{convert|180|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} || {{convert|345|lbft|Nm||abbr=on}} ||Indirect fuel injection\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ford vehicles}}\n{{Ford F-Series}}\n{{Modern North American Ford trucks}}\n{{Ford Motor Company vehicles}}\n\n[[Category:Ford F-Series|8th generation]]\n[[Category:Pickup trucks]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:All-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1986]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:Flexible-fuel vehicles]]\n[[Category:Motor vehicles manufactured in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{main|Ford F-Series}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Eighth generation\n| image = Ford F-150 -- 09-07-2009.jpg\n| manufacturer = [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]]\n| production = (1986\u20131991) USA, Mexico, Canada and Venezuela<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=0OMDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA97&lpg=PA97&dq=ford+f-series+\"august+1986\"+1987#v=onepage&q=ford%20f-series%20%22august%201986%22%201987&f=false |title = Popular Mechanics|publisher = Hearst Magazines|date = August 1986}}</ref> <br>(1987-1992) Australia<ref name=\"au used car advice\">https://www.motoring.com.au/used-car-advice-ford-f-series-1985-92-1945/</ref> <br>(1988-1992) Argentina<br>(1993-1996) Brazil<br> (1993-1996) Argentina (Brazilian trim model)\n| assembly = [[Cuautitlan]], Mexico<br />[[Kansas City, Missouri]], USA<br />[[Norfolk Assembly|Norfolk, Virginia]], USA<br />[[Twin Cities Assembly Plant|St. Paul, Minnesota]], USA<br/> [[General Pacheco]], [[Argentina]]<br />[[S\u00e3o Bernardo do Campo]], [[Brazil]]<br />[[Louisville, Kentucky]], USA<br />[[Wayne, Michigan]], USA<br />[[Oakville, Ontario]], Canada<br />[[Melbourne]], [[Australia]] ([[Broadmeadows Assembly]], [[Ford Australia]]) <ref name=\"au used car advice\" />\n| body_style = 2-door [[pickup truck|pickup]]<br>2-door [[pickup truck#Extended cab|extended cab]] chassis<br />4-door [[chassis cab]]<br>2-door [[pickup truck#No bed (cab and chassis or chassis-cab)|chassis cab]]\n| engine = '''[[Petrol engine|Petrol]]'''<br>{{convert|232|cuin|L|1|disp=flip|abbr=on}} ''[[Ford Essex V6 engine (Canadian)#3.8|Essex]]'' V6 (Ford F-150, Mexico)<br/>{{convert|300|cuin|L|1|disp=flip|abbr=