his.  For the first time, all models were produced with straight-sided Styleside beds; the Flareside bed was discontinued except for a small number of early 1987 models using leftover 1986 beds with new circular fenders. In 1991 Ford premiered the 9th gen tail lights (the white reverse light was decreased in size) on the last year of the 8th generation.\n\n==Trims==\n[[File:F250 utility service truck.jpeg|thumb|Ford F-250 Utility service truck]]\n*Custom - Included: Vinyl upholstery, black steering wheel, chrome front bumper, black grille, hubcaps, foldaway mirrors, and an electronic AM radio with digital clock and two speakers.\n*XL - Added: Cloth and vinyl upholstery, swingaway mirrors, front bumper rub strip, color-keyed floor mat, a door trim panel with map pocket, and a color-keyed headliner.\n*XLT Lariat - Added: Cloth upholstery, chrome grille, sport wheel covers, tinted glass, carpeting, and leather wrapped steering wheel.\n*Nite (1992)\n\nFor 1992, a \"Nite\" trim package was introduced. It included all blacked-out exterior trim, either a pink or blue/purple stripe, and a \"Nite\" decal on the sides of the cargo box.\n\n== Models ==\n[[File:UHI DC5692.JPG|thumb|Ford F-350 [[U-Haul]] truck in [[Hampton, VA]].]]\n\nEighth-generation Ford F-Series models are:\n* '''F-150''': 1/2 ton (6,250&nbsp;lb [[GVWR]] max)\n* '''F-250''': light-duty 3/4 ton (7,700&nbsp;lb GVWR max)\n* '''F-250HD''': 3/4 ton (8,800&nbsp;lb GVWR max)\n* '''F-350''': 1 ton (10,000&nbsp;lb GVWR max)\n* '''F-Super Duty''': Class 4 truck (14,500&nbsp;lb GVWR max)\n\nThe new-for-1987 F-Super Duty was essentially a [[Truck classification#Class 4|Class 4 truck]] built as a chassis cab, with an aftermarket bed (specific to its future use) added after the truck was built. The F-Super Duty came with dual fuel tanks with a dash-mounted toggle switch to switch between each tank, while using only a single fuel gauge. It came with a [[Power take-off|PTO]] used to power attachments, such as winches or a dump bed, directly from the transmission. F-Super Duty models were rated at about {{convert|15000|lb|abbr=on}} [[GVWR]] and came with either the standard 7.5&nbsp;L (460&nbsp;CID) gas V8 or the optional 7.3&nbsp;L (444&nbsp;CID) diesel V8. All wheels were 10-lug with dual wheels in the rear. This model should not be confused with the later [[Ford Super Duty|Super Duty]] commercial line of trucks starting with the 1999 model year.\n\n==Powertrain and chassis==\nIn a move to further update the F-Series engine lineup, the 4.9&nbsp;L inline-6 was converted to fuel injection for 1987. A year later, Ford became the first pickup truck manufacturer to sell a fully non-carbureted engine lineup as the 5.8&nbsp;L V8 and 7.5&nbsp;L V8 also gained [[fuel injection]](the 5.0&nbsp;L V8 had gained fuel injection as an option for 1985 and was made standard in 1986). For 1988, the diesel V8 from International (Navistar) was enlarged to from 420 to 444 cubic inches (6.9 to 7.3 L); this allowed for an increase to {{convert|180|hp|abbr=on}} and {{convert|365|ft.lbf|N.m|abbr=on}} of torque.\n\nWhile the dated 3-speed column-mounted manual transmission was discontinued, much of the rest of the transmission lineup carried over from the 1980-1986 trucks. In 1988, the five-speed ZF S5-42 replaced the Borg-Warner T19 in F-250 and F-350 models. For the F-150 and light-duty F-250, the heavier-duty Borg-Warner T18 4-speed manual remained available, while the Mazda-built [[Mazda M5OD transmission|M5OD]] 5-speed manual was added to the model lineup for 4.9&nbsp;L inline-6 and 5.0&nbsp;L V8-equipped models.\n\nFour-wheel-drive improvements included the addition of automatic locking hubs for the F-150 in 1989. Models with the 5.0L V8 also had an option of a \"Touch Drive\" electronic transfer case.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\nFrom 1980 through 1996, Ford offered a four-wheel-drive swing arm independent front suspension called [[Twin Traction Beam]] (TTB). Based on its two-wheel-drive twin I-beam suspension from 1965, Ford mounted a [[Dana 44]] differential in the driver-side (front) axle beam and transmitted torque to the passenger-side wheel with a double U-jointed axleshaft. Radius arms and coil springs were still used on the F-150, while the four-wheel-drive F-250 and F-350 got leaf springs. The F-250 received TTB [[Dana 50]] axles, and the F-350 a solid [[Dana 60]] axle.\n\n'''Engines:'''\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 88%;\"\n|-\n! Name !! Production !! Engine type/Displacement !! Power !! Torque !! Fuel Delivery\n|-\n|'''[[Ford Straight-6 engine#300|300 Six]]'''||1987-1991 ||{{convert|300|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} I6 || {{convert|145|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} ||{{convert|265|lbft|Nm||abbr=on}} || EFI\n|-\n|'''[[Ford Windsor engine#302|5.0 Windsor]]'''|| 1987-1991 ||{{convert|302|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} V8 ||  {{convert|185|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} || {{convert|270|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}}|| EFI\n|-\n|'''[[Ford Windsor engine#351W|5.8 Windsor]]'''|| 1987 ||  {{convert|351|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} V8  || {{convert|210|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} ||  {{convert|305|lbft|Nm||abbr=on}} ||4-bbl carburetor\n|-\n|'''[[Ford Windsor engine#351W|5.8 Windsor]]'''|| 1988-1991 || {{convert|351|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} V8  || {{convert|210|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} ||  {{convert|315|lbft|Nm||abbr=on}} ||EFI\n\n|-\n|''' [[Ford 385 engine|460 V8]] '''|| 1987 ||{{convert|460|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} V8 || {{convert|225|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} || {{convert|362|lbft|Nm||abbr=on}} ||4-bbl carburetor\n\n|-\n|''' [[Ford 385 engine|460 V8]] '''|| 1988-1991 ||{{convert|460|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} V8 || {{convert|225|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} || {{convert|390|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}}||EFI\n\n|-\n|'''  [[International Harvester IDI#6.9L|International 6.9L IDI V8]]'''|| 1987 ||{{convert|420|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} Diesel V8 || {{convert|170|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} || {{convert|315|lbft|Nm||abbr=on}} ||Indirect fuel injection\n\n|-\n|'''  [[International Harvester IDI#7.3L|International 7.3L IDI V8]] '''|| 1988-1991 ||{{convert|444|cuin|cc|0|abbr=on}} Diesel V8 || {{convert|180|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} || {{convert|345|lbft|Nm||abbr=on}} ||Indirect fuel injection\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ford vehicles}}\n{{Ford F-Series}}\n{{Modern North American Ford trucks}}\n{{Ford Motor Company vehicles}}\n\n[[Category:Ford F-Series|8th generation]]\n[[Category:Pickup trucks]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:All-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:1980s cars]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:Flexible-fuel vehicles]]\n[[Category:Motor vehicles manufactured in the United States]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1986]]\n", "name_user": "TKOIII", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Removed redundant category as per WP:Subcat. Parent category not needed when one of its subcategories is already present.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ford_F-Series_(eighth_generation)"}
{"title_page": "The Daily Illini", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox Newspaper\n| name               = ''Daily Illini''\n| image              = Image:The Daily Illini headerdesktopsd-01 cropped.png\n| image_size         = 250px\n| motto              = \"The independent student newspaper at the University of Illinois\"\n| type               = Daily [[newspaper]]\n| format             = [[Broadsheet]]\n| foundation         = 1871\n| owners             = [[Illini Media]] Company\n| language           = [[English language|English]]\n| headquarters       = University YMCA<br/>1001 S. Wright St,<br/>[[Champaign, Illinois]] 61820\n| publishing_country = [[United States]]\n| circulation        = 20,000 (when classes are in session)\n| ISSN               = 8750-6769\n| website            = [http://www.dailyillini.com www.dailyillini.com]\n| free               = [http://idnc.library.illinois.edu/cgi-bin/illinois?a=cl&cl=CL1&sp=DIL Illinois Digital Newspaper Collections: ''Daily Illini'' (1874-1975)]\n}}\n\nThe '''''Daily Illini''''', commonly known as the '''''DI''''', is a student-run newspaper that has been published for the community of the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]] since 1871. Weekday circulation during fall and spring semesters is 20,000; copies are distributed free at more than 250 locations throughout [[Champaign, Illinois|Champaign\u2013Urbana]].\n\nThe paper is published by [[Illini Media]] Company (IMC), a not-for-profit corporation which owns several other student-run media outlets,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://illinimedia.com/|title=Home|work=Illini Media|access-date=2017-08-25|language=en-US}}</ref> and also operates [[WPGU-FM|WPGU]] 107.1 FM,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wpgu.com/|title=WPGU 107.1 - Champaign's Alternative|website=WPGU 107.1|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-25}}</ref> a student-run commercial radio station. While the IMC has no official ties to the university, university professors and others in the academic community serve on its board of directors. The newspaper\u2019s staff has both full-time professionals and students.\n\nThe paper is published daily online and two days a week in print as a broadsheet.\n\n==Staff==\nThe editorial, business and production departments are staffed by students who are enrolled in a wide variety of degree programs, not just journalism. Several full-time professionals, including the newspaper\u2019s publisher and the advertising and circulation managers, are employees of IMC. Some students are paid for their jobs in reporting, editing, production and advertising, but some of the students work for free, as well.\n\nThe ''Daily Illini'' staff completely changes once per year, known as \"turnover\" in the DI offices. \"Turnover\" means the current group of editors (editor-in-chief, news editors, sports editors, opinions editors and features editors, among others) finish their tenure at the ''DI'' in their current editing position, and a new group of editors fills these positions. The new editor-in-chief is chosen by some members of the IMC, and then the editor-in-chief chooses all of the other editors that will work under him/her.\n\nAt the beginning of each fall and spring semester, the ''DI'' hires new reporters and staff members. All University of Illinois students, regardless of major, are encouraged to apply.\n\n==Awards==\nThe ''DI'' regularly receives first-place awards from the Associated College Press, Society of Professional Journalists, Illinois College Press Association, and Columbia Scholastic Press Association.\n\nIn February 2010, the ''Daily Illini'' was awarded the General Excellence award by the Illinois Collegiate Press Association. Their website, www.dailyillini.com has been named the best college newspaper website in the state for the past four years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.illinimedia.com/DI/DI.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-01-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060219141644/http://www.illinimedia.com/DI/DI.html |archivedate=2006-02-19 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, the ''Daily Illini'' was awarded best newspaper and third best online newspaper in the nation by the [[Associated Collegiate Press]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyillini.com/news/2017/10/29/daily-illini-wins-best-show-national-conference/|title=The Daily Illini wins Best of Show at national conference {{!}} The Daily Illini|last=Report|first=The Daily Illini Staff|website=dailyillini.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, the ''Daily Illini'' was awarded second in General Excellence by the Illinois College Press Association under the leadership of Editor-in-Chief Lillian Barkley.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyillini.com/news/2018/02/17/the-daily-illini-wins-2nd-place-in-general-excellence-at-icpa/|title=The Daily Illini wins second place in general excellence at ICPA {{!}} The Daily Illini|last=Liu|first=Karen|website=dailyillini.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> The newspaper also won best online newspaper by the Illinois College Press Association<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyillini.com/news/2018/02/17/the-daily-illini-wins-2nd-place-in-general-excellence-at-icpa/|title=The Daily Illini wins second place in general excellence at ICPA {{!}} The Daily Illini|last=Liu|first=Karen|website=dailyillini.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> and by the [[Society of Professional Journalists]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spj5conference.com/|title=SPJ Region 5 Conference|website=SPJ Region 5 Conference|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> under the leadership of Managing Editor for Online Jacob Singleton.\n\n==Offices==\nThe newspaper\u2019s office is located at 512 E. Green St. in Champaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://dailyillini.com/contact|title=Contact - The Daily Illini|work=The Daily Illini|access-date=2017-08-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2006, the newspaper along with the other IMC entities, moved east to a new building at 512 E. Green St. in Champaign, closer to campus. In doing so, the company consolidated the offices of WPGU, which had been in a separate location, with the offices of the rest of the IMC entities.\n\nIn May 2018, Illini Media moved from its Green Street location to the University YMCA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyillini.com/opinions/columns-opinions/2018/03/26/new-staff-promises-consistent-presence/|title=New staff promises consistent presence {{!}} The Daily Illini|last=Paeth|first=Abby|website=dailyillini.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Prominent staff emeriti==\nNotable alumni of the newspaper include author and famed [[The New Yorker|New Yorker]] editor [[William Keepers Maxwell Jr.|William Maxwell]], novelist [[Nelson Algren]], [[ABC News]] political director [[Hal Bruno]], ''Rape of Nanking'' author [[Iris Chang]], [[The Simpsons|''Simpsons'']] producer/writer [[Larry Doyle (writer)|Larry Doyle]], film critic [[Roger Ebert]], novelist [[Dave Eggers]], folk singer [[Dan Fogelberg]], ''[[High Times]]'' editor [[Steven Hager]], Playboy founder/CEO [[Hugh Hefner]], attorney [[Albert E. Jenner, Jr.]], columnist [[Robert Novak]], ''Coast to Coast Live'' radio host [[Ian Punnett]], advice columnist [[Dan Savage]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slog.thestranger.com/2006/03/dont_call_me_al |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-07-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303220052/http://slog.thestranger.com/2006/03/dont_call_me_al |archivedate=2016-03-03 }}</ref> film critic [[Gene Shalit]], and several [[Pulitzer Prize]] winners.<ref>[http://www.news-gazette.com/special/answerbook2005/index.cfm?page=story&number=61931]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://alumni.illinimedia.com/famers |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-08-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070727071825/http://alumni.illinimedia.com/famers |archivedate=2007-07-27 }}</ref><ref name=wp>{{cite news|first=Matt|last=Schudel |title=Hal Bruno, former ABC News political director, dies at 83 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/hal-bruno-former-abc-news-political-director-dies-at-83/2011/11/10/gIQAPAPr9M_story.html|work=[[Washington Post]] |publisher= |date=2011-11-10 |accessdate=2011-12-07}}</ref><ref name=nytimes>{{cite news|first=Bruce |last=Weber|title=Hal Bruno, Director of Election Coverage at ABC, Dies at 83|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/10/business/media/hal-bruno-director-of-election-coverage-at-abc-dies-at-83.html|work=[[New York Times]] |publisher= |date=2011-11-09 |accessdate=2011-12-07}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===Anti-semitism===\nIn January 2003, the ''Daily Illini'' printed a letter in its opinion section titled \"Jews Manipulate America.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.illinimedia.com/di/jan03/jan22/opinions/stories/letter03.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-06-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010333/http://www.illinimedia.com/di/jan03/jan22/opinions/stories/letter03.shtml |archivedate=2007-09-27 }}</ref>\nA large amount of criticism followed soon after, calling into question the paper's editorial policy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hfienberg.com/kesher/2003/02/vile-anti-semitic-letter-published-by.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-03-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012164801/http://www.hfienberg.com/kesher/2003/02/vile-anti-semitic-letter-published-by.html |archivedate=2007-10-12 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfty.org/_kd/Items/actions.cfm?action%3DShow%26item_id%3D262%26destination%3DShowItem |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-03-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614155227/http://www.nfty.org/_kd/Items/actions.cfm?action=Show&item_id=262&destination=ShowItem |archivedate=2011-06-14 }}</ref> The editors responded by defending their right to publish it.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}} Critics noted that the publishing of this letter was not surprising to them after the ''Daily Illini''{{'}}s history of publishing other articles that appeared to be anti-Semitic.<ref name=\"camera.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.camera.org/index.asp?x_context=22&x_article=454 |title=At University of Illinois, A Tale of Two Controversies |publisher=CAMERA |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref> Previous letters published in the ''Daily Illini'' have accused Israel of being guilty of genocide and another compared the Jews to Nazis.<ref name=\"camera.org\"/> Moreover, while the ''Daily Illini'' apologized when it published a photo thought to be demeaning to black students, it refused to apologize for publishing a letter claiming that Jews manipulate America.<ref name=\"camera.org\"/>\n\nIn December 2003, the paper published an article by Miriam Sobh called \"Stop Turning a Blind Eye\" <ref>[http://www.illinimedia.com/di/dec03/dec11/opinions/stories/opinions_column02.shtml]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> that contained a quote attributed to Ariel Sharon that was fabricated. (See [[Alleged Ouze Merham interview of Ariel Sharon]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.camera.org/index.asp?x_context=2&x_outlet=131&x_article=676 |title=University of Illinois Columnist Fully Apologizes |publisher=CAMERA |date=2003-12-11 |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>) The author later gave a full apology for using the fabricated quote.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Despite the controversy that occurred from printing the falsely attributed quote the first time, the ''Daily Illini'' printed it a second time on November 19, 2004, in another article.<ref>[https://archive.is/20071107215218/http://media.www.dailyillini.com/media/storage/paper736/news/2004/11/19/Opinions/Friday.Forum.Not.The.Only.One-811161.shtml]</ref>\n\nThe ''DI'' also published an anti-semitic comic strip on November 5, 2004, strip of ''I Hate Pam''.<ref name=\"media.www.dailyillini.com\">[http://media.www.dailyillini.com/media/storage/paper736/news/2004/11/08/Opinions/Editorial.To.Our.Readers-796357.shtml]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> The paper acknowledged in a later editorial that the strip mocked Jews.<ref name=\"media.www.dailyillini.com\"/> The comic was suspended for approximately four weeks.<ref name=\"media.www.dailyillini.com\"/>\n\n===''Jyllands-Posten'' participation===\nThe newspaper's former editor-in-chief Acton Gorton and opinions editor Chuck Prochaska made a controversial decision in February 2006 to print the cartoons from the [[Jyllands-Posten Muhammad cartoons controversy|''Jyllands-Posten'' Muhammad cartoons controversy]] that had previously been printed in Europe and had led to protests around the world and a few instances of violent rioting by offended Muslims. Gorton's column that accompanied the cartoons<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyillini.com/media/paper736/news/2006/02/09/Opinions/Editors.Note-1622265.shtml?norewrite%26sourcedomain%3Dwww.dailyillini.com |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-03-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930015513/http://www.dailyillini.com/media/paper736/news/2006/02/09/Opinions/Editors.Note-1622265.shtml?norewrite&sourcedomain=www.dailyillini.com |archivedate=2007-09-30 }}</ref> was cited to support the first view. Prochaska and Gorton were also criticized by fellow editors in a later editorial<ref>[http://www.dailyillini.com/news/2006/02/13/Opinions/Editorial.Staff.Breaks.Ranks-1610154.shtml]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> for not following protocol in previously discussing their printing, though it was revealed later that some of the staff did know about it in the hours prior to printing. A firestorm of letters and calls from all over the country and the world came into the ''Daily Illini'' expressing both support and outrage. Gorton and Prochaska were suspended with pay for two weeks to investigate whether proper procedures were followed. As of March 14, 2006, Gorton was terminated from the ''Daily Illini''. Prochaska was offered the opportunity to return to his position but refused.\n\n===Editorial accuracy===\nThe ''Daily Illini'' editorials were halted on September 22, 2006, after the September 20, 2006 editorial on the Midnight Madness basketball event<ref>[http://www.dailyillini.com/media/storage/paper736/news/2006/09/20/Opinions/Staff.Editorial.Students.Missing.Out.On.Madness.Tickets-2285918.shtml?norewrite200609261031&sourcedomain=www.dailyillini.com]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> was found to contain misinformation and misinterpretation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.www.dailyillini.com/media/storage/paper736/news/2006/09/22/Opinions/Di.Editorials.Halted.Until.Further.Notice-2302975.shtml?sourcedomain%3Dwww.dailyillini.com%26MIIHost%3Dmedia.collegepublisher.com |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-09-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930015423/http://media.www.dailyillini.com/media/storage/paper736/news/2006/09/22/Opinions/Di.Editorials.Halted.Until.Further.Notice-2302975.shtml?sourcedomain=www.dailyillini.com&MIIHost=media.collegepublisher.com |archivedate=2007-09-30 }}</ref> The paper resumed publishing editorials on October 9, 2006 with an editorial explaining the changes to the way editorials will be researched and published.<ref>[http://www.dailyillini.com/media/storage/paper736/news/2006/10/09/Opinions/Editorial.Editorials.Resume.Under.New.Guidelines-2338150.shtml?norewrite200610090128&sourcedomain=www.dailyillini.com]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> However, even with the new guidelines, on November 29, 2006, the newspaper printed an editorial<ref>[http://www.dailyillini.com/news/2006/11/29/Opinions/Editorial.Military.Conscription.Plan.IllConceived-2511827.shtml]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> calling Representative [[Charles B. Rangel]] a Republican when describing his draft bill. Rangel is a Democrat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rangel.house.gov/bio.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-12-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061207175333/http://rangel.house.gov/bio.shtml |archivedate=2006-12-07 }}</ref>\n\n===Salary Guide publication===\nOn March 9, 2010 the ''Daily Illini'' published a guide to salaries on the Urbana\u2013Champaign campus of the University of Illinois. The information was received through an Illinois Freedom of Information Act request. The online database receives the highest traffic on the site since they started tracking online traffic.\n\n==2012 financial crisis==\nIn February 2012, the ''Daily Illini'' enlisted the help of University of Illinois alumnus and film critic [[Roger Ebert]] to raise funds for the newspaper. The ''Daily Illini'' owed nearly $250,000 loan on their building. The twelve-page broadsheet, which is very costly, played a part in the struggling company.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-ap-il-ebert-collegenews,0,2901071.story |work=Chicago Tribune |title=Topic Galleries |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219004649/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-ap-il-ebert-collegenews,0,2901071.story |archivedate=2012-02-19 }}</ref> As the paper is funded and published by the Illini Media Company, it receives money from the [[University of Illinois at Urbana Champaign]] via mandatory student fees. These fees were approved by the University Board of Trustees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trustees.uillinois.edu/trustees/agenda/January-24-2013--Meeting/011%20jan%20Student%20Fees-2014.pdf |title=Appove Student Fees for Urbanda, Chicago and Springfield Academic Year 2013-14 |publisher=trustees.uillinois.edu |date=24 January 2013 |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alleged Ouze Merham interview of Ariel Sharon]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [http://www.dailyillini.com/ ''Daily Illini'']\n* [http://idnc.library.illinois.edu/cgi-bin/illinois?a=cl&cl=CL1&sp=DIL Illinois Digital Newspaper Collections: ''Daily Illini'' (1874-1975)]\n\n{{University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign campus}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daily Illini, The}}\n[[Category:Publications established in 1871]]\n[[Category:Student newspapers published in Illinois]]\n[[Category:1871 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]]\n[[Category:Champaign, Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox Newspaper\n| name               = ''Daily Illini''\n| image              = Image:The Daily Illini headerdesktopsd-01 cropped.png\n| image_size         = 250px\n| motto              = \"The independent student newspaper at the University of Illinois\"\n| type               = Daily [[newspaper]]\n| format             = [[Broadsheet]]\n| foundation         = 1871\n| owners             = [[Illini Media]] Company\n| language           = [[English language|English]]\n| headquarters       = University YMCA<br/>1001 S. Wright St,<br/>[[Champaign, Illinois]] 61820\n| publishing_country = [[United States]]\n| circulation        = 20,000 (when classes are in session)\n| ISSN               = 8750-6769\n| website            = [http://www.dailyillini.com www.dailyillini.com]\n| free               = [http://idnc.library.illinois.edu/cgi-bin/illinois?a=cl&cl=CL1&sp=DIL Illinois Digital Newspaper Collections: ''Daily Illini'' (1874-1975)]\n}}\n\n'''''The Daily Illini''''', commonly known as the '''''DI''''', is a student-run newspaper that has been published for the community of the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]] since 1871. Weekday circulation during fall and spring semesters is 20,000; copies are distributed free at more than 250 locations throughout [[Champaign, Illinois|Champaign\u2013Urbana]].\n\nThe paper is published by [[Illini Media]] Company, a not-for-profit corporation which owns several other student-run media outlets,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://illinimedia.com/|title=Home|work=Illini Media|access-date=2017-08-25|language=en-US}}</ref> and also operates [[WPGU-FM|WPGU]] 107.1 FM,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wpgu.com/|title=WPGU 107.1 - Champaign's Alternative|website=WPGU 107.1|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-25}}</ref> a student-run commercial radio station. While the IMC has no official ties to the university, university professors and others in the academic community serve on its board of directors. The newspaper\u2019s staff has both full-time professionals and students.\n\nThe paper is published daily online and two days a week in print as a broadsheet.\n\n==Staff==\nThe editorial, business and production departments are staffed by students who are enrolled in a wide variety of degree programs, not just journalism. Several full-time professionals, including the newspaper\u2019s publisher and the advertising and circulation managers, are employees of IMC. Some students are paid for their jobs in reporting, editing, production and advertising, but some of the students work for free, as well.\n\n''The Daily Illini'' staff completely changes once per year, known as \"turnover\" in the DI offices. \"Turnover\" means the current group of editors (editor-in-chief, news editors, sports editors, opinions editors and features editors, among others) finish their tenure at the ''DI'' in their current editing position, and a new group of editors fills these positions. The new editor-in-chief is chosen by some members of the IMC, and then the editor-in-chief chooses all of the other editors that will work under him/her.\n\nAt the beginning of each fall and spring semester, the ''DI'' hires new reporters and staff members. All University of Illinois students, regardless of major, are encouraged to apply.\n\n==Awards==\nThe ''DI'' regularly receives first-place awards from the Associated College Press, Society of Professional Journalists, Illinois College Press Association, and Columbia Scholastic Press Association.\n\nIn February 2010, ''The Daily Illini'' was awarded the General Excellence award by the Illinois Collegiate Press Association. Their website, www.dailyillini.com has been named the best college newspaper website in the state for the past four years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.illinimedia.com/DI/DI.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-01-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060219141644/http://www.illinimedia.com/DI/DI.html |archivedate=2006-02-19 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, ''The Daily Illini'' was awarded best newspaper and third best online newspaper in the nation by the [[Associated Collegiate Press]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyillini.com/news/2017/10/29/daily-illini-wins-best-show-national-conference/|title=The Daily Illini wins Best of Show at national conference {{!}} The Daily Illini|last=Report|first=The Daily Illini Staff|website=dailyillini.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, ''The Daily Illini'' was awarded second in General Excellence by the Illinois College Press Association under the leadership of Editor-in-Chief Lillian Barkley.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyillini.com/news/2018/02/17/the-daily-illini-wins-2nd-place-in-general-excellence-at-icpa/|title=The Daily Illini wins second place in general excellence at ICPA {{!}} The Daily Illini|last=Liu|first=Karen|website=dailyillini.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> The newspaper also won best online newspaper by the Illinois College Press Association<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyillini.com/news/2018/02/17/the-daily-illini-wins-2nd-place-in-general-excellence-at-icpa/|title=The Daily Illini wins second place in general excellence at ICPA {{!}} The Daily Illini|last=Liu|first=Karen|website=dailyillini.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> and by the [[Society of Professional Journalists]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spj5conference.com/|title=SPJ Region 5 Conference|website=SPJ Region 5 Conference|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> under the leadership of Managing Editor for Online Jacob Singleton.\n\n==Offices==\nThe newspaper\u2019s office is located at 512 E. Green St. in Champaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://dailyillini.com/contact|title=Contact - The Daily Illini|work=The Daily Illini|access-date=2017-08-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2006, the newspaper along with the other IMC entities, moved east to a new building at 512 E. Green St. in Champaign, closer to campus. In doing so, the company consolidated the offices of WPGU, which had been in a separate location, with the offices of the rest of the IMC entities.\n\nIn May 2018, Illini Media will move from its Green Street location to the University YMCA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyillini.com/opinions/columns-opinions/2018/03/26/new-staff-promises-consistent-presence/|title=New staff promises consistent presence {{!}} The Daily Illini|last=Paeth|first=Abby|website=dailyillini.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Prominent staff emeriti==\nNotable alumni of the newspaper include author and famed [[The New Yorker|New Yorker]] editor [[William Keepers Maxwell Jr.|William Maxwell]], novelist [[Nelson Algren]], [[ABC News]] political director [[Hal Bruno]], ''Rape of Nanking'' author [[Iris Chang]], [[The Simpsons|''Simpsons'']] producer/writer [[Larry Doyle (writer)|Larry Doyle]], film critic [[Roger Ebert]], novelist [[Dave Eggers]], folk singer [[Dan Fogelberg]], ''[[High Times]]'' editor [[Steven Hager]], Playboy founder/CEO [[Hugh Hefner]], attorney [[Albert E. Jenner, Jr.]], columnist [[Robert Novak]], ''Coast to Coast Live'' radio host [[Ian Punnett]], advice columnist [[Dan Savage]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slog.thestranger.com/2006/03/dont_call_me_al |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-07-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303220052/http://slog.thestranger.com/2006/03/dont_call_me_al |archivedate=2016-03-03 }}</ref> film critic [[Gene Shalit]], and several [[Pulitzer Prize]] winners.<ref>[http://www.news-gazette.com/special/answerbook2005/index.cfm?page=story&number=61931]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://alumni.illinimedia.com/famers |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-08-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070727071825/http://alumni.illinimedia.com/famers |archivedate=2007-07-27 }}</ref><ref name=wp>{{cite news|first=Matt|last=Schudel |title=Hal Bruno, former ABC News political director, dies at 83 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/hal-bruno-former-abc-news-political-director-dies-at-83/2011/11/10/gIQAPAPr9M_story.html|work=[[Washington Post]] |publisher= |date=2011-11-10 |accessdate=2011-12-07}}</ref><ref name=nytimes>{{cite news|first=Bruce |last=Weber|title=Hal Bruno, Director of Election Coverage at ABC, Dies at 83|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/10/business/media/hal-bruno-director-of-election-coverage-at-abc-dies-at-83.html|work=[[New York Times]] |publisher= |date=2011-11-09 |accessdate=2011-12-07}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===Anti-semitism===\nIn January 2003, ''The Daily Illini'' printed a letter in its opinion section titled \"Jews Manipulate America.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.illinimedia.com/di/jan03/jan22/opinions/stories/letter03.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-06-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010333/http://www.illinimedia.com/di/jan03/jan22/opinions/stories/letter03.shtml |archivedate=2007-09-27 }}</ref>\nA large amount of criticism followed soon after, calling into question the paper's editorial policy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hfienberg.com/kesher/2003/02/vile-anti-semitic-letter-published-by.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-03-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012164801/http://www.hfienberg.com/kesher/2003/02/vile-anti-semitic-letter-published-by.html |archivedate=2007-10-12 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfty.org/_kd/Items/actions.cfm?action%3DShow%26item_id%3D262%26destination%3DShowItem |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-03-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614155227/http://www.nfty.org/_kd/Items/actions.cfm?action=Show&item_id=262&destination=ShowItem |archivedate=2011-06-14 }}</ref> The editors responded by defending their right to publish it.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}} Critics noted that the publishing of this letter was not surprising to them after ''The Daily Illini''{{'}}s history of publishing other articles that appeared to be anti-Semitic.<ref name=\"camera.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.camera.org/index.asp?x_context=22&x_article=454 |title=At University of Illinois, A Tale of Two Controversies |publisher=CAMERA |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref> Previous letters published in ''The Daily Illini'' have accused Israel of being guilty of genocide and another compared the Jews to Nazis.<ref name=\"camera.org\"/> Moreover, while ''The Daily Illini'' apologized when it published a photo thought to be demeaning to black students, it refused to apologize for publishing a letter claiming that Jews manipulate America.<ref name=\"camera.org\"/>\n\nIn December 2003, the paper published an article by Miriam Sobh called \"Stop Turning a Blind Eye\" <ref>[http://www.illinimedia.com/di/dec03/dec11/opinions/stories/opinions_column02.shtml]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> that contained a quote attributed to Ariel Sharon that was fabricated. (See [[Alleged Ouze Merham interview of Ariel Sharon]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.camera.org/index.asp?x_context=2&x_outlet=131&x_article=676 |title=University of Illinois Columnist Fully Apologizes |publisher=CAMERA |date=2003-12-11 |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>) The author later gave a full apology for using the fabricated quote.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Despite the controversy that occurred from printing the falsely attributed quote the first time, The Daily Illini printed it a second time on November 19, 2004, in another article.<ref>[https://archive.is/20071107215218/http://media.www.dailyillini.com/media/storage/paper736/news/2004/11/19/Opinions/Friday.Forum.Not.The.Only.One-811161.shtml]</ref>\n\nThe ''DI'' also published an anti-semitic comic strip on November 5, 2004, strip of ''I Hate Pam''.<ref name=\"media.www.dailyillini.com\">[http://media.www.dailyillini.com/media/storage/paper736/news/2004/11/08/Opinions/Editorial.To.Our.Readers-796357.shtml]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> The paper acknowledged in a later editorial that the strip mocked Jews.<ref name=\"media.www.dailyillini.com\"/> The comic was suspended for approximately four weeks.<ref name=\"media.www.dailyillini.com\"/>\n\n===''Jyllands-Posten'' participation===\nThe newspaper's former editor-in-chief Acton Gorton and opinions editor Chuck Prochaska made a controversial decision in February 2006 to print the cartoons from the [[Jyllands-Posten Muhammad cartoons controversy|''Jyllands-Posten'' Muhammad cartoons controversy]] that had previously been printed in Europe and had led to protests around the world and a few instances of violent rioting by offended Muslims. Gorton's column that accompanied the cartoons<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyillini.com/media/paper736/news/2006/02/09/Opinions/Editors.Note-1622265.shtml?norewrite%26sourcedomain%3Dwww.dailyillini.com |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-03-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930015513/http://www.dailyillini.com/media/paper736/news/2006/02/09/Opinions/Editors.Note-1622265.shtml?norewrite&sourcedomain=www.dailyillini.com |archivedate=2007-09-30 }}</ref> was cited to support the first view. Prochaska and Gorton were also criticized by fellow editors in a later editorial<ref>[http://www.dailyillini.com/news/2006/02/13/Opinions/Editorial.Staff.Breaks.Ranks-1610154.shtml]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> for not following protocol in previously discussing their printing, though it was revealed later that some of the staff did know about it in the hours prior to printing. A firestorm of letters and calls from all over the country and the world came into ''The Daily Illini'' expressing both support and outrage. Gorton and Prochaska were suspended with pay for two weeks to investigate whether proper procedures were followed. As of March 14, 2006, Gorton was terminated from ''The Daily Illini''. Prochaska was offered the opportunity to return to his position but refused.\n\n===Editorial accuracy===\n''The Daily Illini'' editorials were halted on September 22, 2006, after the September 20, 2006 editorial on the Midnight Madness basketball event<ref>[http://www.dailyillini.com/media/storage/paper736/news/2006/09/20/Opinions/Staff.Editorial.Students.Missing.Out.On.Madness.Tickets-2285918.shtml?norewrite200609261031&sourcedomain=www.dailyillini.com]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> was found to contain misinformation and misinterpretation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.www.dailyillini.com/media/storage/paper736/news/2006/09/22/Opinions/Di.Editorials.Halted.Until.Further.Notice-2302975.shtml?sourcedomain%3Dwww.dailyillini.com%26MIIHost%3Dmedia.collegepublisher.com |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-09-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930015423/http://media.www.dailyillini.com/media/storage/paper736/news/2006/09/22/Opinions/Di.Editorials.Halted.Until.Further.Notice-2302975.shtml?sourcedomain=www.dailyillini.com&MIIHost=media.collegepublisher.com |archivedate=2007-09-30 }}</ref> The paper resumed publishing editorials on October 9, 2006 with an editorial explaining the changes to the way editorials will be researched and published.<ref>[http://www.dailyillini.com/media/storage/paper736/news/2006/10/09/Opinions/Editorial.Editorials.Resume.Under.New.Guidelines-2338150.shtml?norewrite200610090128&sourcedomain=www.dailyillini.com]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> However, even with the new guidelines, on November 29, 2006, the newspaper printed an editorial<ref>[http://www.dailyillini.com/news/2006/11/29/Opinions/Editorial.Military.Conscription.Plan.IllConceived-2511827.shtml]{{dead link|date=October 2016}}</ref> calling Representative [[Charles B. Rangel]] a Republican when describing his draft bill. Rangel is a Democrat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rangel.house.gov/bio.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-12-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061207175333/http://rangel.house.gov/bio.shtml |archivedate=2006-12-07 }}</ref>\n\n===Salary Guide publication===\nOn March 9, 2010 ''The Daily Illini'' published a guide to salaries on the Urbana\u2013Champaign campus of the University of Illinois. The information was received through an Illinois Freedom of Information Act request. The online database receives the highest traffic on the site since they started tracking online traffic.\n\n==2012 financial crisis==\nIn February 2012, ''The Daily Illini'' enlisted the help of University of Illinois alumnus and film critic [[Roger Ebert]] to raise funds for the newspaper. The ''Daily Illini'' owed nearly $250,000 loan on their building. The 12 page broadsheet, which is very costly, played a part in the struggling company.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-ap-il-ebert-collegenews,0,2901071.story |work=Chicago Tribune |title=Topic Galleries |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219004649/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-ap-il-ebert-collegenews,0,2901071.story |archivedate=2012-02-19 }}</ref> As the paper is funded and published by the Illini Media Company, it receives money from the [[University of Illinois at Urbana Champaign]] via mandatory student fees. These fees were approved by the University Board of Trustees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trustees.uillinois.edu/trustees/agenda/January-24-2013--Meeting/011%20jan%20Student%20Fees-2014.pdf |title=Appove Student Fees for Urbanda, Chicago and Springfield Academic Year 2013-14 |publisher=trustees.uillinois.edu |date=24 January 2013 |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alleged Ouze Merham interview of Ariel Sharon]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [http://www.dailyillini.com/ ''Daily Illini'']\n* [http://idnc.library.illinois.edu/cgi-bin/illinois?a=cl&cl=CL1&sp=DIL Illinois Digital Newspaper Collections: ''Daily Illini'' (1874-1975)]\n\n{{University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign campus}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daily Illini, The}}\n[[Category:Publications established in 1871]]\n[[Category:Student newspapers published in Illinois]]\n[[Category:1871 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]]\n[[Category:Champaign, Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Thrakkx", "label": "safe", "comment": "Editing: \"The\" is not a part of the newspaper name; therefore, it is not capitalized or italicized.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Daily_Illini"}
{"title_page": "LX Xander", "text_new": "'''LX Xander''' (born '''Alexander William Larkman''' on May 23rd, 1990) is a [[music producer]] and remixer from the UK.<ref name=source>[https://thesource.com/2017/08/17/on-the-rise-spooky-producer-lx-xander/ \"On The Rise: Spooky Producer LX Xander\" The Source Article]</ref> He is also the CEO and founder of Ghostcraft Music.<ref>[http://www.ghostcraftmusic.com Official Ghostcraft Music Website]</ref> \n\nXander has produced tracks featuring artists such as [[Royce da 5'9\"]], [[Angela Mazzanti]] and [[Future (rapper)|Future]], as well as remixing [[Alien Ant Farm]] for [[Cleopatra Records]].<ref name=source/><ref>[https://www.ghostcraftmusic.com/angela-mazzanti Angela Mazzanti Biography on Ghostcraft Music Website]</ref><ref name=discogs>[https://www.discogs.com/artist/7111721-LX-Xander LX Xander on Discogs.com]</ref><ref>[https://www.lxxander.com LX Xander Official Biography]</ref> He also created the ''Big Pile o' Shite'' VST, a music software that helps others to emulate his signature sound.<ref>[https://www.modernproducers.com/products/spooker-vst?variant=5452316508191 Spooker VST on ModernProducers.com]</ref> \n\nIn 2017, Xander produced 'The Red Room' featuring dark hip-hop poster boy [[Hopsin]] and later in the same year, 'Afterlife', featuring superstar [[Snoop Dogg]].<ref name=discogs/><ref>[https://www.thehypemagazine.com/2017/10/exclusive-snoop-dogg-afterlife-produced-by-spooky-hip-hop-producer-lx-xander/ \"Exclusive: Snoop Dogg \u2018Afterlife\u2019 produced by spooky Hip Hop producer LX Xander\" The Hype Magazine Article]</ref> In March 2018, Yaydo released the song 'Ubetcha' through Ghostcraft (co-produced by LX Xander), which went on to appear on [[Viceland]]'s [[Most Expensivest]], hosted by [[2 Chainz]] and [[VH1]]'s [[Black Ink Crew: Chicago]].<ref>[https://www.benzinga.com/pressreleases/18/03/r11445462/yaydo-signs-with-ghostcraft-releases-video-for-ubetcha \"Yaydo Signs With Ghostcraft & Releases Video For \"Ubetcha\"\" on Benzinga.com]</ref><ref>[https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/2-chainz-most-expensivest-sex-dolls/ \"2 Chainz Gets Freaked Out by Touching the \u2018Most Expensivest\u2019 Sex Dolls\" Clip from ''Most Expensivest'' with 'Ubetcha' playing in background]</ref><ref>[https://www.instagram.com/p/B0mssFOHfRc/ Clip from ''Black Ink Crew: Chicago'' posted on LX Xander's Instagram page with 'Ubetcha' playing in background]</ref> \n\nReleased in May 2018, LX also contributed to the project ''The Whoodlum Ball'', a Billboard-charting, multi-artist, producer-driven album by [[Mike Smith (record producer)|Mike Smith]] and [[Jonathan Hay (publicist)|Jonathan Hay]], with [[DJ Whoo Kid]].<ref>[https://ediblesmagazine.com/politics/hip-hop-a-weed-friendly-senator-and-a-playwright-the-story-of-how-i-made-it-to-8-billboard-charts-with-a-cannabis-poem/ \"Hip-Hop, A Weed-Friendly Senator And A Playwright: The Story Of How I Made It To 8 Billboard Charts With A Cannabis Poem\" Edibles Magazine Article]</ref><ref>[https://medium.com/authority-magazine/im-excited-about-the-higher-than-normal-number-of-women-executives-in-the-industry-with-author-8a44e1606d09 \"\u201cI\u2019m Excited About The Higher-Than-Normal Number Of Women Executives In The Industry\u201d With Author Javier Hasse\" Medium Article]</ref><ref>[https://www.billboard.com/music/mike-smith/chart-history/TLP/song/1079236 Official [[Billboard charts|Billboard]] Website]</ref> \n\nXander also produced two songs for rapper, model and influencer [[Angela Mazzanti]], both of which were released by [[Cleopatra Records]], one in October 2018 featuring [[Rick Ross]] and another in April 2019 featuring [[Caskey (rapper)|Caskey]].<ref>[http://cleorecs.com/home/releases/ Official Cleopatra Records Website]</ref><ref>[https://www.worldstarhiphop.com/videos/video.php?v=wshhcpKI4046a2Sor2jH \"Angela Mazzanti Feat. Rick Ross - We So Mob\" Angela Mazzanti 'So Mob' ft. Rick Ross on WorldStar]</ref><ref>[https://www.worldstarhiphop.com/videos/video.php?v=wshhI0z0r3AqHkX21P3w \"Angela Mazzanti & Caskey - The Greatest\" Angela Mazzanti 'The Greatest' ft. Caskey on WorldStar]</ref>\n\nIn an interview published on [[Medium (website)|Medium]] in April 2020, LX Lardman confirmed that he is a massive fan of Big Macs and that he holds the record for most calories stored as fat in the face from consuming fast food in 2019. <ref>[https://medium.com/@Ontheriseartists/an-interview-with-polyamorous-cult-leader-billboard-charting-music-producer-lx-xander-ed721ac88568 \"An Interview With Polyamorous Cult Leader & Billboard-charting Music Producer LX Xander\"]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Xander, LX}}\n[[Category:British record producers]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{UK-record-producer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''LX Xander''' (born '''Alexander William Larkman''' on May 23rd, 1990) is a [[music producer]] and remixer from the UK.<ref name=source>[https://thesource.com/2017/08/17/on-the-rise-spooky-producer-lx-xander/ \"On The Rise: Spooky Producer LX Xander\" The Source Article]</ref> He is also the CEO and founder of Ghostcraft Music.<ref>[http://www.ghostcraftmusic.com Official Ghostcraft Music Website]</ref> \n\nXander has produced tracks featuring artists such as [[Royce da 5'9\"]], [[Angela Mazzanti]] and [[Future (rapper)|Future]], as well as remixing [[Alien Ant Farm]] for [[Cleopatra Records]].<ref name=source/><ref>[https://www.ghostcraftmusic.com/angela-mazzanti Angela Mazzanti Biography on Ghostcraft Music Website]</ref><ref name=discogs>[https://www.discogs.com/artist/7111721-LX-Xander LX Xander on Discogs.com]</ref><ref>[https://www.lxxander.com LX Xander Official Biography]</ref> He also created the ''Spooker'' VST, a music software that helps others to emulate his signature sound.<ref>[https://www.modernproducers.com/products/spooker-vst?variant=5452316508191 Spooker VST on ModernProducers.com]</ref> \n\nIn 2017, Xander produced 'The Red Room' featuring dark hip-hop poster boy [[Hopsin]] and later in the same year, 'Afterlife', featuring superstar [[Snoop Dogg]].<ref name=discogs/><ref>[https://www.thehypemagazine.com/2017/10/exclusive-snoop-dogg-afterlife-produced-by-spooky-hip-hop-producer-lx-xander/ \"Exclusive: Snoop Dogg \u2018Afterlife\u2019 produced by spooky Hip Hop producer LX Xander\" The Hype Magazine Article]</ref> In March 2018, Yaydo released the song 'Ubetcha' through Ghostcraft (co-produced by LX Xander), which went on to appear on [[Viceland]]'s [[Most Expensivest]], hosted by [[2 Chainz]] and [[VH1]]'s [[Black Ink Crew: Chicago]].<ref>[https://www.benzinga.com/pressreleases/18/03/r11445462/yaydo-signs-with-ghostcraft-releases-video-for-ubetcha \"Yaydo Signs With Ghostcraft & Releases Video For \"Ubetcha\"\" on Benzinga.com]</ref><ref>[https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/2-chainz-most-expensivest-sex-dolls/ \"2 Chainz Gets Freaked Out by Touching the \u2018Most Expensivest\u2019 Sex Dolls\" Clip from ''Most Expensivest'' with 'Ubetcha' playing in background]</ref><ref>[https://www.instagram.com/p/B0mssFOHfRc/ Clip from ''Black Ink Crew: Chicago'' posted on LX Xander's Instagram page with 'Ubetcha' playing in background]</ref> \n\nReleased in May 2018, LX also contributed to the project ''The Whoodlum Ball'', a Billboard-charting, multi-artist, producer-driven album by [[Mike Smith (record producer)|Mike Smith]] and [[Jonathan Hay (publicist)|Jonathan Hay]], with [[DJ Whoo Kid]].<ref>[https://ediblesmagazine.com/politics/hip-hop-a-weed-friendly-senator-and-a-playwright-the-story-of-how-i-made-it-to-8-billboard-charts-with-a-cannabis-poem/ \"Hip-Hop, A Weed-Friendly Senator And A Playwright: The Story Of How I Made It To 8 Billboard Charts With A Cannabis Poem\" Edibles Magazine Article]</ref><ref>[https://medium.com/authority-magazine/im-excited-about-the-higher-than-normal-number-of-women-executives-in-the-industry-with-author-8a44e1606d09 \"\u201cI\u2019m Excited About The Higher-Than-Normal Number Of Women Executives In The Industry\u201d With Author Javier Hasse\" Medium Article]</ref><ref>[https://www.billboard.com/music/mike-smith/chart-history/TLP/song/1079236 Official [[Billboard charts|Billboard]] Website]</ref> \n\nXander also produced two songs for rapper, model and influencer [[Angela Mazzanti]], both of which were released by [[Cleopatra Records]], one in October 2018 featuring [[Rick Ross]] and another in April 2019 featuring [[Caskey (rapper)|Caskey]].<ref>[http://cleorecs.com/home/releases/ Official Cleopatra Records Website]</ref><ref>[https://www.worldstarhiphop.com/videos/video.php?v=wshhcpKI4046a2Sor2jH \"Angela Mazzanti Feat. Rick Ross - We So Mob\" Angela Mazzanti 'So Mob' ft. Rick Ross on WorldStar]</ref><ref>[https://www.worldstarhiphop.com/videos/video.php?v=wshhI0z0r3AqHkX21P3w \"Angela Mazzanti & Caskey - The Greatest\" Angela Mazzanti 'The Greatest' ft. Caskey on WorldStar]</ref>\n\nIn an interview published on [[Medium (website)|Medium]] in April 2020, LX confirmed that he is [[polyamory|polyamorous]] and that he is the leader of a [[cult]]. <ref>[https://medium.com/@Ontheriseartists/an-interview-with-polyamorous-cult-leader-billboard-charting-music-producer-lx-xander-ed721ac88568 \"An Interview With Polyamorous Cult Leader & Billboard-charting Music Producer LX Xander\"]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Xander, LX}}\n[[Category:British record producers]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{UK-record-producer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "194.207.236.95", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LX_Xander"}
{"title_page": "Crossover (automobile)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n[[File:2014 Nissan Rogue S AWD front left.jpg|thumb|2014 [[Nissan Rogue]], an example of a crossover]]\n\nA '''crossover'''\u2014also called a '''CUV''' (crossover utility vehicle)\u2014is a type of vehicle with [[unibody]] construction.<ref>{{cite web|title=AutoMotion Blog Top 10 Crossover SUVs In The 2013 Vehicle Dependability Study |url= http://autos.jdpower.com/content/blog-post/JyWb4Fp/top-10-crossover-suvs-in-the-2013-vehicle-dependability-study.htm |work=JD Power |date=21 March 2013  |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130819081305/http://autos.jdpower.com/content/blog-post/JyWb4Fp/top-10-crossover-suvs-in-the-2013-vehicle-dependability-study.htm |archivedate=19 August 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Crossovers are often based on a platform shared with a passenger car; compared to truck-based [[Sport utility vehicle|SUVs]], they typically have better interior comfort, a more comfortable ride, and superior fuel economy, but lower off-road capability.<ref name=\"intelli\"/><ref name=\"cnn1\"/><ref name=\"autos.aol.com\"/> Poor off-road capability is compounded by many crossovers being sold without [[all-wheel drive]], which challenges their definition as \"sports utility vehicles\".\n\nFurthermore, there are various inconsistencies about whether some vehicles are considered crossovers or SUVs; therefore, the term \"SUV\" is often used as a catch-all for both crossovers and compact SUVs.<ref>{{cite web |title=5 Reasons to Buy a Crossover Vehicle |url= https://smartstuff.howstuffworks.com/5-reasons-buy-crossover-vehicle/ |website=HowStuffWorks |accessdate=15 September 2019 |date=22 October 2018 |quote=\u201cCrossover\u201d is now used almost interchangeably with \u201ccompact SUV,\u201d but some new vehicles are pushing those boundaries.}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States {{as of|2006|lc=on}}, crossover models comprised more than 50% of the overall SUV market.<ref name=\":0\" /> Crossovers have also become increasingly popular in Europe since the early 2010s.\n\nForerunners of the modern crossover include the 1977 [[Matra Rancho]] and [[AMC Eagle]] introduced in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autotrader.com/car-news/amc-eagle-no-seriously-this-was-the-first-crossover-suv-265257|title=AMC Eagle: No, Seriously, This Was the First Crossover SUV|last1=Gold|first1=Aaron|date=May 2017|website=www.autotrader.com|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Definition ==\nThe difference between crossovers and other SUVs is sometimes defined as a crossover being built using a [[unibody]] platform (the type used by most passenger cars), while an SUV is built using a [[body-on-frame]] platform (the type used by off-road vehicles and light trucks).<ref>{{cite web |title=Difference between a crossover vehicle and SUV? |url=https://www.hertzcarsales.co.uk/used-cars-blog-difference-between-a-crossover-vehicle-and-suv |website=www.hertzcarsales.co.uk |accessdate=2019-04-22 |language=en |date=2019-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=What is the Difference Between Crossovers and SUVs? \u00ab Harbin Automotive |url=https://www.harbinautomotive.com/blog/what-is-the-difference-between-crossovers-and-suvs/ |website=www.harbinautomotive.com |accessdate=2019-04-22 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"intelli\">{{cite web |title=Smart Buying Essentials What is a Crossover Vehicle? |work=Intellichoice |url= http://www.intellichoice.com/carBuying101/what-is-a-crossover |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110717054551/http://www.intellichoice.com/carBuying101/what-is-a-crossover |archivedate=17 July 2011 |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=What\u2019s the Difference Between an SUV, a Crossover, & a CUV? |url=https://thenewswheel.com/whats-the-difference-between-an-suv-a-crossover-a-cuv/ |website=www.thenewswheel.com |accessdate=2019-04-22 |date=2017-03-30}}</ref> However, these definitions are often blurred in practice, since unibody vehicles are also often referred to as SUVs.<ref>{{cite web |title=SUV vs. Crossover: What\u2019s the Difference? |url=https://www.autotrader.com/car-shopping/suv-vs-crossover-whats-difference-215843 |website=www.autotrader.com |accessdate=2019-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=SUVs vs. Crossovers: What's the Difference? |url=https://cars.usnews.com/cars-trucks/best-cars-blog/2016/09/suvs-vs-crossovers-whats-the-difference |website=www.usnews.com |accessdate=2019-04-22}}</ref> Also, \"crossover\" is a relatively recent term, and early unibody SUVs (such as the 1984 Jeep Cherokee) are rarely called crossovers. Due to these inconsistencies, the term SUV is often used as an umbrella term for both crossovers and SUVs.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Difference Between SUVs and Crossover Cars |url=https://www.carwriteups.co.uk/2018/04/difference-suvs-crossovers-cars/ |website=www.carwriteups.co.uk |accessdate=2019-04-22 |date=2018-04-09}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn1\"/><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.caranddriver.com/comparisons/2013-bmw-x3-xdrive28i-vs-2013-audi-q5-20t-2013-land-rover-range-rover-evoque-comparison-test |date=February 2013 |title=2013 BMW X3 xDrive28i vs. 2013 Audi Q5 2.0T, 2013 Land Rover Range Rover Evoque |first=Daniel |last=Fund |journal=Car and Driver |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOutside of the United States, the term \"crossover\" tends to be used for [[C-segment]] ([[compact car|compact]]) or smaller vehicles, with large unibody vehicles\u2014such as the [[Audi Q7]], [[BMW X7]] and [[Volkswagen Touareg]]\u2014usually known as SUVs rather than crossovers. In the United Kingdom, a crossover is sometimes defined as a [[hatchback]] with raised [[ride height]] and SUV-like styling features.<ref>{{cite web |title=What's the difference between a crossover, SUV and 4x4? |url=https://www.carbuyer.co.uk/tips-and-advice/159974/whats-the-difference-between-a-crossover-suv-and-4x4 |website=www.carbuyer.co.uk |accessdate=2019-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=SUV vs Crossover: What are the Differences and Similarities? |url=https://www.leasefetcher.co.uk/blog/suv-vs-crossover-differences |website=www.leasefetcher.co.uk |accessdate=2019-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{main article|Sport_utility_vehicle#History {{!}} Sport utility vehicle # History}}\nIntroduced in 1979, the [[AMC Eagle]] is retroactively considered to be the first dedicated crossover automobile that made its debut prior to the terms \"SUV\" or \"crossover\" being coined.<ref name=\"howstuffworks.com\">{{cite web |title=Who coined the term 'crossover vehicle?' |url=https://auto.howstuffworks.com/car-models/crossover-cars/term-crossover-vehicle.htm |website=www.howstuffworks.com |accessdate=8 December 2018 |date=13 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.autotrader.com/car-news/amc-eagle-no-seriously-this-was-the-first-crossover-suv-265257 |title=AMC Eagle: No, Seriously, This Was the First Crossover SUV |first=Aaron |last=Gold |date=May 2017 |work=Auto Trader |accessdate=5 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Sherman |first=Don |title=All-Wheel-Drive Revisited: AMC's 1980 Eagle pioneered the cross-over SUV |journal=Automotive Industries |date=1 February 2001 |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-69103689.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130501140243/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-69103689.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= 1 May 2013 |accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.automotivehalloffame.org/honoree/roy-lunn/ |title=Roy Lunn - Inducted 2016 |work=Automobile Hall of Fame |accessdate=5 July 2017}}</ref> The mass-market Eagle model line was based on a [[unibody]] passenger car platform, with fully automatic four-wheel drive and a raised ride height.<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=MAEAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA90 |last=Jacobs |first=Ed |title=Passenger-car comfort, plus 4wd security for all-weather security |journal=Popular Science |date=September 1979 |volume=215 |issue=3 |pages=90\u201391 |accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.mustangandfords.com/news/1608-roy-lunn-inducted-into-automotive-hall-of-fame/ |title=Roy Lunn Inducted Into Automotive Hall Of Fame |first=Mark |last=Houlahan |work=Mustang Monthly |date=3 August 2016 |accessdate=5 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Norbye |first=Jan P. |title=Half-Hour History of Four-Wheel-Drive Autos |url= https://www.hemmings.com/blog/2009/12/13/sia-flashback-half-hour-history-of-four-wheel-drive-autos/#&gid=1&pid=1 |website=www.hemmings.com |publisher=Special Interest Autos |date=October 1980 |accessdate=6 December 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Carney |first=Dan |title=AMC Eagle, the unlikely trail-blazer |url=http://www.bbc.com/autos/story/20130925-the-unlikely-awd-trail-blazer |publisher=BBC |quote=1980 AMC Eagle, the first full-time all-wheel-drive passenger car to reach mass production. |accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Flory, Jr. |first=J. Kelly |title=American Cars, 1973-1980: Every Model, Year by Year |date=2012 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786443529 |page=775 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=PV1uzCfmJDgC&pg=PA775&lpg=PA775 |accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nSome cite the [[front-wheel drive]] 1977 [[Matra Rancho]] as a slightly earlier forerunner to the modern crossover.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matra Rancho: the original crossover |date=6 March 2015 |work=The Telegraph |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cars/classic/matra-rancho-the-original-crossover/ |accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThough it is not part of the modern linear evolution, and only fifteen were built, some stretch the definition and history of the \"crossover\" to regard the off-road racing 1936 [[Opel Gel\u00e4ndesportwagen]] as the first of the class.<ref>{{cite news |last=Carlsson |first=M\u00e5rten |url=http://www.klassiker.nu/reportage/opel-terrangsportbil |title=Opel Gel\u00e4ndesportwagen, en Cross-over fr\u00e5n 1936 |trans-title=Opel Gel\u00e4ndesportwagen, a Crossover from 1936 |work=Klassiker |location=Sweden |language=Swedish |date=26 June 2018 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe 1994 [[Toyota RAV4]] is credited as the model that expanded the concept and the crossover market segment.<ref name=\"conquered\">{{cite journal|last=Madrigal|first=Alexis C.|date=10 July 2014|title=Why Crossovers conquered the American Highway|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/07/how-the-crossover-conquered-americas-automobile-market/374061/|journal=The Atlantic|location=US|access-date=6 July 2017}}</ref> Essentially a shrunken SUV, the RAV4 was based on the platform used by the [[Toyota Corolla]].<ref name=\"autos.aol.com\">{{cite web |title=Crossover 101 |url= http://autos.aol.com/article/crossovers-101/ |website=www.aol.com |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160416223830/http://autos.aol.com/article/crossovers-101/ |archivedate=16 April 2016 |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> \n\n{{gallery\n|mode=packed |height=150 |align=center\n| File: 1977 Simca Matra Rancho.jpg\n| 1977 [[Matra Rancho|Matra-Simca Rancho]]\n| File: 1982 AMC Eagle 4-door wagon two-tone 03.jpg\n| 1979-1987 [[AMC Eagle]]\n| File: 1995 Toyota RAV4 (SXA11R) Cruiser wagon (2015-07-14) 01.jpg\n| 1995 [[Toyota RAV4]]\n}}\n\n== Size categories ==\n=== Subcompact crossover ===\nSubcompact crossovers are usually based on the platform of a [[Subcompact car|subcompact]] (also known as [[supermini]] or [[B-segment]]) passenger car.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topgear.com/uk/car-news/peugeot-crossover-renault-clio-2012-04-23|title=Prepare for the mini-SUV invasion\u2026|date=April 24, 2012|work=Top Gear|accessdate=August 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/car-review/nissan/juke/first-drives/nissan-juke-1.5-dci-tekna|title=Nissan Juke 1.5dCi Tekna Review|work=Autocar|accessdate=May 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jukeownersclub.co.uk/news/Auto-Express-First-Drive.asp|title=Auto Express - First Drive Nissan Juke|work=jukeownersclub|accessdate=May 24, 2017}}</ref> They typically have limited off-road capabilities, with some differing from the standard hatchback model with only a bumper hinge and more ground clearance.\n\n=== Compact crossover ===\nCompact crossovers are usually based on the platform of a [[compact car|compact]] (also known as [[C-segment]]) passenger car. The first compact crossovers included the 1994 [[Toyota_RAV4#First_generation_(XA10;_1994\u20132000)|Toyota RAV4]],<ref name=\"conquered\" /> 1995 [[Honda_CR-V#First_generation_(1995\u20132001)|Honda CR-V]], 2000 [[Nissan_X-Trail#First_generation_(T30;_2000\u20132007)|Nissan X-Trail]], 2000 [[Mazda_Tribute#First_generation_(2000\u20132007)|Mazda Tribute]] and 2001 [[Ford_Escape#First_generation_(2001\u20132007)|Ford Escape]].\n\nThe number of compact crossover models offered has rapidly increased since 2010. In 2019, it was stated by [[Car and Driver]] that \"so many of these vehicles are crowding the marketplace, simply sorting through them can be a daunting task\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/flipbook/practical-matters-every-compact-crossover-suv-ranked-from-worst-to-best#1|title=Practicality Matters: Every Compact Crossover SUV Ranked from Worst to Best|website=Car and Driver|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Sales ==\n\n=== Europe ===\nSince the early 2010s, sales of crossover-type vehicles have been increasing in Europe.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Schmitt |first1=Bertel |title=European Class Struggle: SUV-Crossovers De-class Golf-Class, Emissions Edge Up |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bertelschmitt/2017/03/03/european-class-struggle-suv-crossovers-de-class-golf-class-emissions-edge-up/#67b2bf791543 |website=Forbes |date=3 March 2017 |accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref> By 2017, European sales of compact and mid-sized crossover models continued to surge.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Demandt |first1=Bart |title=European sales 2017 compact & midsized crossover segments |url=http://carsalesbase.com/european-sales-2017-compact-midsized-crossover-segments/ |website=carsalesbase.com |date=16 February 2018 |accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\nSales of crossovers increased 30% between 2003 and 2005.<ref name=\"cnn1\">{{cite news |title= GM and Ford's New Cross to Bear |work= CNN Money |first= Chris |last= Isidore |date= 9 January 2006 |url= http://money.cnn.com/2006/01/09/Autos/detroit_crossovers/index.htm |accessdate= 27 July 2015}}</ref> By 2006, the segment came into strong visibility in the U.S., when crossover sales \"made up more than 50% of the overall SUV market\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |title=Crossover vehicles pass up SUVs on road to growing sales |newspaper=USA Today |date=3 May 2006 |first= Sharon Silke |last=Carty |url= http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/autos/2006-05-03-crossover-usat_x.htm |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref> Sales increased in 2007 by 16%.<ref name=\"wsj1\">{{cite web|title=Crossover Market Is Thinly Sliced |first=Joseph B.|last=White |work=The Wall Street Journal Blogs |date=14 January 2008 |url= https://blogs.wsj.com/autoshow/2008/01/14/crossover-market-is-thinly-sliced/ |accessdate=27 July 2015 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 2013, the [[Audi Q5]] became [[Audi]]'s second best-selling vehicle in the United States market after the [[Audi A4]] sedan.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.caranddriver.com/comparisons/2013-bmw-x3-xdrive28i-vs-2013-audi-q5-20t-2013-land-rover-range-rover-evoque-comparison-test |title=2013 BMW X3 xDrive28i vs. 2013 Audi Q5 2.0T, 2013 Land Rover Range Rover Evoque |date=February 2013 |first=Daniel |last=Pund |work=Car and Driver |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref> Around half of [[Lexus]]' sales volume has come from its SUVs since the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2011/autos/1112/gallery.most-disliked-cars.fortune/7.html |title=The most disliked cars of 2011 |first=Alex |last=Taylor III |date=19 December 2011 |work=CNN |accessdate=27 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426163936/http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2011/autos/1112/gallery.most-disliked-cars.fortune/7.html |archivedate=26 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAmerican manufacturers were initially slow to switch from their emphasis on light truck-based SUVs, and foreign automakers developed crossovers targeting the U.S. market as an alternative to [[Station wagon|station wagons]] that were unpopular there. But by the 2010 model year, American car manufacturers had caught up.<ref name=\"cnn1\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Car classification]]\n* [[Compact SUV]]\n* [[List of SUVs]]\n* [[Mini SUV]]\n* [[Minivan]]\n* [[Recreational vehicle]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Cars}}\n{{Automobile configuration}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Crossover sport utility vehicles| ]]\n[[Category:Automotive design]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n[[File:2014 Nissan Rogue S AWD front left.jpg|thumb|2014 [[Nissan Rogue]], an example of a crossover]]\n\nA '''crossover'''\u2014also called a '''CUV''' (crossover utility vehicle)\u2014is a type of vehicle with [[unibody]] construction.<ref>{{cite web|title=AutoMotion Blog Top 10 Crossover SUVs In The 2013 Vehicle Dependability Study |url= http://autos.jdpower.com/content/blog-post/JyWb4Fp/top-10-crossover-suvs-in-the-2013-vehicle-dependability-study.htm |work=JD Power |date=21 March 2013  |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130819081305/http://autos.jdpower.com/content/blog-post/JyWb4Fp/top-10-crossover-suvs-in-the-2013-vehicle-dependability-study.htm |archivedate=19 August 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Crossovers are often based on a platform shared with a passenger car; compared to truck-based [[Sport utility vehicle|SUVs]], they typically have better interior comfort, a more comfortable ride, and superior fuel economy, but lower off-road capability.<ref name=\"intelli\"/><ref name=\"cnn1\"/><ref name=\"autos.aol.com\"/> Poor off-road capability is compounded by many crossovers being sold without [[all-wheel drive]], which challenges their definition as \"sports utility vehicles\".\n\nFurthermore, there are various inconsistencies about whether some vehicles are considered crossovers or SUVs; therefore, the term \"SUV\" is often used as a catch-all for both crossovers and compact SUVs.<ref>{{cite web |title=5 Reasons to Buy a Crossover Vehicle |url= https://smartstuff.howstuffworks.com/5-reasons-buy-crossover-vehicle/ |website=HowStuffWorks |accessdate=15 September 2019 |date=22 October 2018 |quote=\u201cCrossover\u201d is now used almost interchangeably with \u201ccompact SUV,\u201d but some new vehicles are pushing those boundaries.}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States {{as of|2006|lc=on}}, crossover models comprised more than 50% of the overall SUV market.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} Crossovers have also become increasingly popular in Europe since the early 2010s.\n\nForerunners of the modern crossover include the 1977 [[Matra Rancho]] and [[AMC Eagle]] introduced in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autotrader.com/car-news/amc-eagle-no-seriously-this-was-the-first-crossover-suv-265257|title=AMC Eagle: No, Seriously, This Was the First Crossover SUV|last1=Gold|first1=Aaron|date=May 2017|website=www.autotrader.com|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Definition ==\nThe difference between crossovers and other SUVs is sometimes defined as a crossover being built using a [[unibody]] platform (the type used by most passenger cars), while an SUV is built using a [[body-on-frame]] platform (the type used by off-road vehicles and light trucks).<ref>{{cite web |title=Difference between a crossover vehicle and SUV? |url=https://www.hertzcarsales.co.uk/used-cars-blog-difference-between-a-crossover-vehicle-and-suv |website=www.hertzcarsales.co.uk |accessdate=2019-04-22 |language=en |date=2019-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=What is the Difference Between Crossovers and SUVs? \u00ab Harbin Automotive |url=https://www.harbinautomotive.com/blog/what-is-the-difference-between-crossovers-and-suvs/ |website=www.harbinautomotive.com |accessdate=2019-04-22 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"intelli\">{{cite web |title=Smart Buying Essentials What is a Crossover Vehicle? |work=Intellichoice |url= http://www.intellichoice.com/carBuying101/what-is-a-crossover |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110717054551/http://www.intellichoice.com/carBuying101/what-is-a-crossover |archivedate=17 July 2011 |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=What\u2019s the Difference Between an SUV, a Crossover, & a CUV? |url=https://thenewswheel.com/whats-the-difference-between-an-suv-a-crossover-a-cuv/ |website=www.thenewswheel.com |accessdate=2019-04-22 |date=2017-03-30}}</ref> However, these definitions are often blurred in practice, since unibody vehicles are also often referred to as SUVs.<ref>{{cite web |title=SUV vs. Crossover: What\u2019s the Difference? |url=https://www.autotrader.com/car-shopping/suv-vs-crossover-whats-difference-215843 |website=www.autotrader.com |accessdate=2019-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=SUVs vs. Crossovers: What's the Difference? |url=https://cars.usnews.com/cars-trucks/best-cars-blog/2016/09/suvs-vs-crossovers-whats-the-difference |website=www.usnews.com |accessdate=2019-04-22}}</ref> Also, \"crossover\" is a relatively recent term, and early unibody SUVs (such as the 1984 Jeep Cherokee) are rarely called crossovers. Due to these inconsistencies, the term SUV is often used as an umbrella term for both crossovers and SUVs.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Difference Between SUVs and Crossover Cars |url=https://www.carwriteups.co.uk/2018/04/difference-suvs-crossovers-cars/ |website=www.carwriteups.co.uk |accessdate=2019-04-22 |date=2018-04-09}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn1\"/><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.caranddriver.com/comparisons/2013-bmw-x3-xdrive28i-vs-2013-audi-q5-20t-2013-land-rover-range-rover-evoque-comparison-test |date=February 2013 |title=2013 BMW X3 xDrive28i vs. 2013 Audi Q5 2.0T, 2013 Land Rover Range Rover Evoque |first=Daniel |last=Fund |journal=Car and Driver |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOutside of the United States, the term \"crossover\" tends to be used for [[C-segment]] ([[compact car|compact]]) or smaller vehicles, with large unibody vehicles\u2014such as the [[Audi Q7]], [[BMW X7]] and [[Volkswagen Touareg]]\u2014usually known as SUVs rather than crossovers. In the United Kingdom, a crossover is sometimes defined as a [[hatchback]] with raised [[ride height]] and SUV-like styling features.<ref>{{cite web |title=What's the difference between a crossover, SUV and 4x4? |url=https://www.carbuyer.co.uk/tips-and-advice/159974/whats-the-difference-between-a-crossover-suv-and-4x4 |website=www.carbuyer.co.uk |accessdate=2019-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=SUV vs Crossover: What are the Differences and Similarities? |url=https://www.leasefetcher.co.uk/blog/suv-vs-crossover-differences |website=www.leasefetcher.co.uk |accessdate=2019-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{main article|Sport_utility_vehicle#History {{!}} Sport utility vehicle # History}}\nIntroduced in 1979, the [[AMC Eagle]] is retroactively considered to be the first dedicated crossover automobile that made its debut prior to the terms \"SUV\" or \"crossover\" being coined.<ref name=\"howstuffworks.com\">{{cite web |title=Who coined the term 'crossover vehicle?' |url=https://auto.howstuffworks.com/car-models/crossover-cars/term-crossover-vehicle.htm |website=www.howstuffworks.com |accessdate=8 December 2018 |date=13 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.autotrader.com/car-news/amc-eagle-no-seriously-this-was-the-first-crossover-suv-265257 |title=AMC Eagle: No, Seriously, This Was the First Crossover SUV |first=Aaron |last=Gold |date=May 2017 |work=Auto Trader |accessdate=5 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Sherman |first=Don |title=All-Wheel-Drive Revisited: AMC's 1980 Eagle pioneered the cross-over SUV |journal=Automotive Industries |date=1 February 2001 |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-69103689.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130501140243/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-69103689.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= 1 May 2013 |accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.automotivehalloffame.org/honoree/roy-lunn/ |title=Roy Lunn - Inducted 2016 |work=Automobile Hall of Fame |accessdate=5 July 2017}}</ref> The mass-market Eagle model line was based on a [[unibody]] passenger car platform, with fully automatic four-wheel drive and a raised ride height.<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=MAEAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA90 |last=Jacobs |first=Ed |title=Passenger-car comfort, plus 4wd security for all-weather security |journal=Popular Science |date=September 1979 |volume=215 |issue=3 |pages=90\u201391 |accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.mustangandfords.com/news/1608-roy-lunn-inducted-into-automotive-hall-of-fame/ |title=Roy Lunn Inducted Into Automotive Hall Of Fame |first=Mark |last=Houlahan |work=Mustang Monthly |date=3 August 2016 |accessdate=5 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Norbye |first=Jan P. |title=Half-Hour History of Four-Wheel-Drive Autos |url= https://www.hemmings.com/blog/2009/12/13/sia-flashback-half-hour-history-of-four-wheel-drive-autos/#&gid=1&pid=1 |website=www.hemmings.com |publisher=Special Interest Autos |date=October 1980 |accessdate=6 December 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Carney |first=Dan |title=AMC Eagle, the unlikely trail-blazer |url=http://www.bbc.com/autos/story/20130925-the-unlikely-awd-trail-blazer |publisher=BBC |quote=1980 AMC Eagle, the first full-time all-wheel-drive passenger car to reach mass production. |accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Flory, Jr. |first=J. Kelly |title=American Cars, 1973-1980: Every Model, Year by Year |date=2012 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786443529 |page=775 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=PV1uzCfmJDgC&pg=PA775&lpg=PA775 |accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nSome cite the [[front-wheel drive]] 1977 [[Matra Rancho]] as a slightly earlier forerunner to the modern crossover.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matra Rancho: the original crossover |date=6 March 2015 |work=The Telegraph |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cars/classic/matra-rancho-the-original-crossover/ |accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThough it is not part of the modern linear evolution, and only fifteen were built, some stretch the definition and history of the \"crossover\" to regard the off-road racing 1936 [[Opel Gel\u00e4ndesportwagen]] as the first of the class.<ref>{{cite news |last=Carlsson |first=M\u00e5rten |url=http://www.klassiker.nu/reportage/opel-terrangsportbil |title=Opel Gel\u00e4ndesportwagen, en Cross-over fr\u00e5n 1936 |trans-title=Opel Gel\u00e4ndesportwagen, a Crossover from 1936 |work=Klassiker |location=Sweden |language=Swedish |date=26 June 2018 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe 1994 [[Toyota RAV4]] is credited as the model that expanded the concept and the crossover market segment.<ref name=\"conquered\">{{cite journal|last=Madrigal|first=Alexis C.|date=10 July 2014|title=Why Crossovers conquered the American Highway|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/07/how-the-crossover-conquered-americas-automobile-market/374061/|journal=The Atlantic|location=US|access-date=6 July 2017}}</ref> Essentially a shrunken SUV, the RAV4 was based on the platform used by the [[Toyota Corolla]].<ref name=\"autos.aol.com\">{{cite web |title=Crossover 101 |url= http://autos.aol.com/article/crossovers-101/ |website=www.aol.com |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160416223830/http://autos.aol.com/article/crossovers-101/ |archivedate=16 April 2016 |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> \n\n{{gallery\n|mode=packed |height=150 |align=center\n| File: 1977 Simca Matra Rancho.jpg\n| 1977 [[Matra Rancho|Matra-Simca Rancho]]\n| File: 1982 AMC Eagle 4-door wagon two-tone 03.jpg\n| 1979-1987 [[AMC Eagle]]\n| File: 1995 Toyota RAV4 (SXA11R) Cruiser wagon (2015-07-14) 01.jpg\n| 1995 [[Toyota RAV4]]\n}}\n\n== Size categories ==\n=== Subcompact crossover ===\nSubcompact crossovers are usually based on the platform of a [[Subcompact car|subcompact]] (also known as [[supermini]] or [[B-segment]]) passenger car.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topgear.com/uk/car-news/peugeot-crossover-renault-clio-2012-04-23|title=Prepare for the mini-SUV invasion\u2026|date=April 24, 2012|work=Top Gear|accessdate=August 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/car-review/nissan/juke/first-drives/nissan-juke-1.5-dci-tekna|title=Nissan Juke 1.5dCi Tekna Review|work=Autocar|accessdate=May 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jukeownersclub.co.uk/news/Auto-Express-First-Drive.asp|title=Auto Express - First Drive Nissan Juke|work=jukeownersclub|accessdate=May 24, 2017}}</ref> They typically have limited off-road capabilities, with some differing from the standard hatchback model with only a bumper hinge and more ground clearance.\n\n=== Compact crossover ===\nCompact crossovers are usually based on the platform of a [[compact car|compact]] (also known as [[C-segment]]) passenger car. The first compact crossovers included the 1994 [[Toyota_RAV4#First_generation_(XA10;_1994\u20132000)|Toyota RAV4]],<ref name=\"conquered\" /> 1995 [[Honda_CR-V#First_generation_(1995\u20132001)|Honda CR-V]], 2000 [[Nissan_X-Trail#First_generation_(T30;_2000\u20132007)|Nissan X-Trail]], 2000 [[Mazda_Tribute#First_generation_(2000\u20132007)|Mazda Tribute]] and 2001 [[Ford_Escape#First_generation_(2001\u20132007)|Ford Escape]].\n\nThe number of compact crossover models offered has rapidly increased since 2010. In 2019, it was stated by [[Car and Driver]] that \"so many of these vehicles are crowding the marketplace, simply sorting through them can be a daunting task\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/flipbook/practical-matters-every-compact-crossover-suv-ranked-from-worst-to-best#1|title=Practicality Matters: Every Compact Crossover SUV Ranked from Worst to Best|website=Car and Driver|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Sales ==\n\n=== Europe ===\nSince the early 2010s, sales of crossover-type vehicles have been increasing in Europe.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Schmitt |first1=Bertel |title=European Class Struggle: SUV-Crossovers De-class Golf-Class, Emissions Edge Up |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bertelschmitt/2017/03/03/european-class-struggle-suv-crossovers-de-class-golf-class-emissions-edge-up/#67b2bf791543 |website=Forbes |date=3 March 2017 |accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref> By 2017, European sales of compact and mid-sized crossover models continued to surge.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Demandt |first1=Bart |title=European sales 2017 compact & midsized crossover segments |url=http://carsalesbase.com/european-sales-2017-compact-midsized-crossover-segments/ |website=carsalesbase.com |date=16 February 2018 |accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\nSales of crossovers increased 30% between 2003 and 2005.<ref name=\"cnn1\">{{cite news |title= GM and Ford's New Cross to Bear |work= CNN Money |first= Chris |last= Isidore |date= 9 January 2006 |url= http://money.cnn.com/2006/01/09/Autos/detroit_crossovers/index.htm |accessdate= 27 July 2015}}</ref> By 2006, the segment came into strong visibility in the U.S., when crossover sales \"made up more than 50% of the overall SUV market\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Crossover vehicles pass up SUVs on road to growing sales |newspaper=USA Today |date=3 May 2006 |first= Sharon Silke |last=Carty |url= http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/autos/2006-05-03-crossover-usat_x.htm |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref> Sales increased in 2007 by 16%.<ref name=\"wsj1\">{{cite web|title=Crossover Market Is Thinly Sliced |first=Joseph B.|last=White |work=The Wall Street Journal Blogs |date=14 January 2008 |url= https://blogs.wsj.com/autoshow/2008/01/14/crossover-market-is-thinly-sliced/ |accessdate=27 July 2015 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 2013, the [[Audi Q5]] became [[Audi]]'s second best-selling vehicle in the United States market after the [[Audi A4]] sedan.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.caranddriver.com/comparisons/2013-bmw-x3-xdrive28i-vs-2013-audi-q5-20t-2013-land-rover-range-rover-evoque-comparison-test |title=2013 BMW X3 xDrive28i vs. 2013 Audi Q5 2.0T, 2013 Land Rover Range Rover Evoque |date=February 2013 |first=Daniel |last=Pund |work=Car and Driver |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref> Around half of [[Lexus]]' sales volume has come from its SUVs since the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2011/autos/1112/gallery.most-disliked-cars.fortune/7.html |title=The most disliked cars of 2011 |first=Alex |last=Taylor III |date=19 December 2011 |work=CNN |accessdate=27 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426163936/http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2011/autos/1112/gallery.most-disliked-cars.fortune/7.html |archivedate=26 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAmerican manufacturers were initially slow to switch from their emphasis on light truck-based SUVs, and foreign automakers developed crossovers targeting the U.S. market as an alternative to [[Station wagon|station wagons]] that were unpopular there. But by the 2010 model year, American car manufacturers had caught up.<ref name=\"cnn1\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Car classification]]\n* [[Compact SUV]]\n* [[List of SUVs]]\n* [[Mini SUV]]\n* [[Minivan]]\n* [[Recreational vehicle]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Cars}}\n{{Automobile configuration}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Crossover sport utility vehicles| ]]\n[[Category:Automotive design]]\n", "name_user": "Rdhded", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crossover_(automobile)"}
{"title_page": "Rate (mathematics)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Rate (disambiguation){{!}}Rate}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2015}}\nFollow my mom [[mathematics]], a '''rate''' is the [[ratio]] between two related [[quantity|quantities]] in different units.<ref>See Webster's new international dictionary of the English language, second edition, unabridged.  Merriam Webster Co. 2016. p.2065 definition 3.\nwhile this definition doesn't say \"related\" and while the ratio of two non-related quantities is technically a ratio, such a ratio has little (if any meaning).  For example, what would be the utility of finding the ratio of such unrelated numbers as ratio of the weight of ones residence to an integer selected at random between -10<sup>\u22129</sup> and +10<sup>9</sup>?</ref>  If the denominator of the ratio is expressed as a single unit of one of these quantities, and if it is assumed that this quantity can be changed systematically (i.e., is an [[independent variable]]), then the numerator of the ratio expresses the corresponding ''rate of change'' in the other [[dependent variable|(dependent)]] variable.  \n\npeyton is goated\", such as [[speed]], [[heart rate]] and [[flux]]. Ratios that have a non-time denominator include [[exchange rate]]s, [[literacy rate]]s and [[electric field]] (in volts/meter).\n\nIn describing the units of a rate, the word \"per\" is used to separate the units of the two measurements used to calculate the rate (for example a [[heart rate]] is expressed \"beats per minute\"). A rate defined using two numbers of the same [[Units of measurement|units]] (such as [[tax rate]]s) or counts (such as [[literacy rate]]) will result in a [[dimensionless quantity]], which can be expressed as a [[percentage]] (for example, the global [[literacy rate]] in 1998 was 80%) or [[fraction (mathematics)|fraction]] or as a [[multiple (mathematics)|multiple]].\n\nOften ''rate'' is a synonym of [[rhythm]] or [[frequency]], a count per second (i.e., [[Hertz]]); e.g., [[radio frequencies]] or [[heart rate]] or [[sample rate]].\n\n==Introduction==\n\nRates and ratios often vary with time, location, particular element (or subset) of a set of objects, etc.  Thus they are often [[Function (mathematics)|mathematical functions]].  For example, velocity v (distance tracity on segment i (v is a function of index i).  Here each segment i, of the trip is a subset of the trip route.\n\nA rate (or ratio) may often be thought of as an output-input ratio,  [[benefit-cost ratio]], all considered in the broad sense. For example, miles per hour in transportation is the output (or benefit) in terms of miles of travel, which one gets from spending an hour (a cost in time) of traveling (at this velocity).\n\nA set of sequential indices i may be used to enumerate elements (or subsets) of a set of ratios under study.  For example, in finance, one could define i by assigning consecutive integers to companies, to political subdivisions (such as states), to different investments, etc.  The reason for using indices i, is so a set of ratios (i=0,N) can be used in an equation so as to calculate a function of the rates such as an average of a set of ratios.  For example, the average velocity found from the set of v<sub>i</sub>'s mentioned above.  Finding averages may involve using weighted averages and possibly using the [[Harmonic mean]].\n\nA ratio r=a/b has both a numerator a and a denominator b. a and/or b may be a [[real number]] or [[integer]].  The inverse of a ratio r is 1/r  = b/a.\n\nRates occur in many areas of real life. For example:\n''How fast are you driving?'' Miles per hour is a rate. ''What interest does your savings account pay you?'' Interest paid / year is a rate.\n\n==Rate of change{{anchor|Of change}}==\nConsider the case where the numerator <math>f</math> of a rate is a function <math>f(a)</math> where <math>a</math> happens to be the denominator of the rate <math>\\delta f/\\delta a</math>.  A rate of change of <math>f</math> with respect to <math>a</math> (where <math>a</math> is incremented by <math>h</math>) can be formally defined in two ways:<ref>{{cite book|last1=Adams |first1=Robert A. |title=Calculus: A Complete Course|edition=3rd |year=1995 |publisher=Addison-Wesley Publishers Ltd. |isbn=0-201-82823-5 |page=129}}</ref>\n: <math>\n\\begin{align}\n\\mbox{Average rate of change} &= \\frac{f(a + h) - f(a)}{h}\\\\\n\\mbox{Instantaneous rate of change} &= \\lim_{h \\to 0}\\frac{f(a + h) - f(a)}{h}\n\\end{align}\n</math>\nwhere ''f(x)'' is the function with respect to ''x'' over the interval from ''a'' to ''a''+''h''. An instantaneous rate of change is equivalent to a [[derivative]].\n\nAn example to contrast the differences between the unit rates are ''average'' and ''instantaneous'' definitions: the [[speed]] of a car can be calculated:\n# An average rate can be calculated using the total distance travelled between ''a'' and ''b'', divided by the travel time\n# An instantaneous rate can be determined by viewing a [[speedometer]].\nHowever these two formulas do not directly apply where either the [[Range (mathematics)|range]] or the [[Domain of a function|domain]] of <math>f()</math> is a set of integers or where there is no given formula (function) for finding the numerator of the ratio from its denominator.\n\n==Temporal rates{{anchor|Temporal}}==\n{{main cat|Temporal rates}}\n{{see also|Time derivative}}\nIn chemistry and physics:\n* [[Speed]], the rate of change of [[Position (vector)|position]], or the change of position per unit of time\n* [[Acceleration]], the rate of change in speed, or the change in speed per unit of time\n* [[Power (physics)|Power]], the rate of doing [[Work (physics)|work]], or the amount of [[energy (physics)|energy]] transferred per unit time\n* [[Frequency]], the number of occurrences of a repeating event per unit of time\n* [[Reaction rate]], the speed at which chemical reactions occur\n* [[Volumetric flow rate]], the volume of fluid which passes through a given surface per unit of time; e.g., [[cubic meters per second]]\n\n===Counts-per-time rates===\n{{main article|Frequency|Aperiodic frequency}}\n* [[Radioactive decay]], the amount of radioactive material in which one nucleus decays per second, measured in [[Becquerel]]s\n\nIn computing:\n* [[Bit rate]], the number of bits that are conveyed or processed by a computer per unit of time\n* [[Symbol rate]], the number of symbol changes (signalling events) made to the transmission medium per second\n* [[Sampling rate]], the number of samples (signal measurements) per second\n\nMiscellaneous definitions:\n* [[Rate of reinforcement]], number of reinforcements per unit of time, usually per minute\n* [[Heart rate]], usually measured in beats per minute\n\n==Economics/finance rates/ratios==\n* [[Exchange rate]], how much one currency is worth in terms of the other\n* [[Inflation rate]], ratio of the change in the general price level during a year to the starting price level\n* [[Interest rate]], the price a borrower pays for the use of money they do not own (ratio of payment to amount borrowed)\n* [[Price\u2013earnings ratio]],  market price per share of stock divided by annual earnings per share\n* [[Rate of return]], the ratio of money gained or lost on an investment relative to the amount of money invested\n* [[Tax rate]], the tax amount divided by the taxable income\n* [[Unemployment rate]], the ratio of the number of people who are unemployed to the number in the labor force \n* [[Wage | Wage Rate]], the amount paid for working a given amount of time (or doing a standard amount of accomplished work) (ratio of payment to time)\n\n==Other rates==\n* [[Birth rate]], and [[mortality rate]], the number of births or deaths scaled to the size of that population, per unit of time\n* [[Literacy rate]], the proportion of the population over age fifteen that can read and write\n* [[Sex ratio]] or Gender ratio, the ratio of males to females in a population\n\n==See also==\n* [[Derivative]]\n* [[Gradient]]\n* [[Harmonic mean]]\n* [[Hertz]]\n* [[Slope]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rate (Mathematics)}}\n[[Category:Measurement]]\n[[Category:Rates| ]]\n\n[[de:Rate]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Rate (disambiguation){{!}}Rate}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2015}}\nIn [[mathematics]], a '''rate''' is the [[ratio]] between two related [[quantity|quantities]] in different units.<ref>See Webster's new international dictionary of the English language, second edition, unabridged.  Merriam Webster Co. 2016. p.2065 definition 3.\nwhile this definition doesn't say \"related\" and while the ratio of two non-related quantities is technically a ratio, such a ratio has little (if any meaning).  For example, what would be the utility of finding the ratio of such unrelated numbers as ratio of the weight of ones residence to an integer selected at random between -10<sup>\u22129</sup> and +10<sup>9</sup>?</ref>  If the denominator of the ratio is expressed as a single unit of one of these quantities, and if it is assumed that this quantity can be changed systematically (i.e., is an [[independent variable]]), then the numerator of the ratio expresses the corresponding ''rate of change'' in the other [[dependent variable|(dependent)]] variable.  \n\npeyton is goated\", such as [[speed]], [[heart rate]] and [[flux]]. Ratios that have a non-time denominator include [[exchange rate]]s, [[literacy rate]]s and [[electric field]] (in volts/meter).\n\nIn describing the units of a rate, the word \"per\" is used to separate the units of the two measurements used to calculate the rate (for example a [[heart rate]] is expressed \"beats per minute\"). A rate defined using two numbers of the same [[Units of measurement|units]] (such as [[tax rate]]s) or counts (such as [[literacy rate]]) will result in a [[dimensionless quantity]], which can be expressed as a [[percentage]] (for example, the global [[literacy rate]] in 1998 was 80%) or [[fraction (mathematics)|fraction]] or as a [[multiple (mathematics)|multiple]].\n\nOften ''rate'' is a synonym of [[rhythm]] or [[frequency]], a count per second (i.e., [[Hertz]]); e.g., [[radio frequencies]] or [[heart rate]] or [[sample rate]].\n\n==Introduction==\n\nRates and ratios often vary with time, location, particular element (or subset) of a set of objects, etc.  Thus they are often [[Function (mathematics)|mathematical functions]].  For example, velocity v (distance tracity on segment i (v is a function of index i).  Here each segment i, of the trip is a subset of the trip route.\n\nA rate (or ratio) may often be thought of as an output-input ratio,  [[benefit-cost ratio]], all considered in the broad sense. For example, miles per hour in transportation is the output (or benefit) in terms of miles of travel, which one gets from spending an hour (a cost in time) of traveling (at this velocity).\n\nA set of sequential indices i may be used to enumerate elements (or subsets) of a set of ratios under study.  For example, in finance, one could define i by assigning consecutive integers to companies, to political subdivisions (such as states), to different investments, etc.  The reason for using indices i, is so a set of ratios (i=0,N) can be used in an equation so as to calculate a function of the rates such as an average of a set of ratios.  For example, the average velocity found from the set of v<sub>i</sub>'s mentioned above.  Finding averages may involve using weighted averages and possibly using the [[Harmonic mean]].\n\nA ratio r=a/b has both a numerator a and a denominator b. a and/or b may be a [[real number]] or [[integer]].  The inverse of a ratio r is 1/r  = b/a.\n\nRates occur in many areas of real life. For example:\n''How fast are you driving?'' Miles per hour is a rate. ''What interest does your savings account pay you?'' Interest paid / year is a rate.\n\n==Rate of change{{anchor|Of change}}==\nConsider the case where the numerator <math>f</math> of a rate is a function <math>f(a)</math> where <math>a</math> happens to be the denominator of the rate <math>\\delta f/\\delta a</math>.  A rate of change of <math>f</math> with respect to <math>a</math> (where <math>a</math> is incremented by <math>h</math>) can be formally defined in two ways:<ref>{{cite book|last1=Adams |first1=Robert A. |title=Calculus: A Complete Course|edition=3rd |year=1995 |publisher=Addison-Wesley Publishers Ltd. |isbn=0-201-82823-5 |page=129}}</ref>\n: <math>\n\\begin{align}\n\\mbox{Average rate of change} &= \\frac{f(a + h) - f(a)}{h}\\\\\n\\mbox{Instantaneous rate of change} &= \\lim_{h \\to 0}\\frac{f(a + h) - f(a)}{h}\n\\end{align}\n</math>\nwhere ''f(x)'' is the function with respect to ''x'' over the interval from ''a'' to ''a''+''h''. An instantaneous rate of change is equivalent to a [[derivative]].\n\nAn example to contrast the differences between the unit rates are ''average'' and ''instantaneous'' definitions: the [[speed]] of a car can be calculated:\n# An average rate can be calculated using the total distance travelled between ''a'' and ''b'', divided by the travel time\n# An instantaneous rate can be determined by viewing a [[speedometer]].\nHowever these two formulas do not directly apply where either the [[Range (mathematics)|range]] or the [[Domain of a function|domain]] of <math>f()</math> is a set of integers or where there is no given formula (function) for finding the numerator of the ratio from its denominator.\n\n==Temporal rates{{anchor|Temporal}}==\n{{main cat|Temporal rates}}\n{{see also|Time derivative}}\nIn chemistry and physics:\n* [[Speed]], the rate of change of [[Position (vector)|position]], or the change of position per unit of time\n* [[Acceleration]], the rate of change in speed, or the change in speed per unit of time\n* [[Power (physics)|Power]], the rate of doing [[Work (physics)|work]], or the amount of [[energy (physics)|energy]] transferred per unit time\n* [[Frequency]], the number of occurrences of a repeating